{"title_page": "Jack and Jill (magazine)", "text_new": "{{Infobox magazine\n| logo            = \n| logo_size       = \n| image_file      = Jack & Jill March 2008.jpg\n| image_size      = <!-- (defaults to user thumbnail size if no size is stated) -->\n| image_alt       = \n| image_caption   = March 2008 cover\n| editor          = \n| editor_title    = \n| previous_editor = \n| staff_writer    = \n| photographer    = \n| category        = Children's magazine\n| frequency       = Bimonthly\n| circulation     = \n| publisher       = \n| founder         = \n| founded         = \n| firstdate       = {{Start date|1938|month}} \n| company         = [[Saturday Evening Post]] Society\n| country         = United States\n| based           = [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]\n| language        = English\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.uskidsmags.com/magazines/jack-and-jill/}}\n| issn            = 0021-3829\n| oclc            = \n}}\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\n'''''Jack and Jill''''' is an [[United States|American]] [[bimonthly]] [[magazine]] for children 6 to 12 years old that takes its title from the [[nursery rhyme]] of [[Jack and Jill (nursery rhyme)|the same name]]. It features stories and educational activities.\n\nThe magazine features nonfiction articles, short stories, poems, games, comics, recipes, crafts, and more. Having been continuously produced for 80 years, it is one of the oldest American magazines for kids.\n\n==Mission==\nAs part of the Children's Better Health Institute\u2014a division of the Saturday Evening Post Society Inc., a 501 (c)(3) nonprofit charitable organization\u2014''Jack and Jill''<!-- -->'s mission is to promote the healthy physical, educational, creative, social, and emotional growth of children in a format that is engaging, stimulating, and entertaining for children ages 6 to 12.<ref>[http://www.uskidsmags.com/about/ U.S. Kids Magazines Official Website]</ref>\n\n==History==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Jack and Jill 1938.jpg|thumb|left|The first issue of ''Jack and Jill'' in 1938.]] -->\n''Jack and Jill'' magazine was launched by [[Curtis Publishing Company]] in 1938. It was the first addition to the Curtis line of magazines since it purchased ''[[Country Gentleman]]'' in 1911. The first editor of ''Jack and Jill'' was [[Ada Campbell Rose]] daughter-in-law of [[Philip Sheridan Rose]], the editor of ''Country Gentleman''.<ref>\"Jack and Jill\". ''Time''. Oct. 24, 1938.</ref> It was headquartered in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Wesley Francis Amar|title=Children's Magazines Today|journal=The Elementary English Review|date=November 1943|volume=20|issue=7|jstor=41382721}}</ref> The magazine's circulation grew to half a million before [[newsagent|newsstand]] sales (but not subscriptions) were suspended during [[World War II]] due to paper shortages. Newsstand sales returned in 1948.<ref>\"[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,853363,00.html Up the hill]\". ''Time'', November 8, 1948. U.S. copyright renewals:  [http://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/cce/cache/pdrn1969f396.gif 1941], [http://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/cce/cache/pdrn1970f412.gif 1942], [http://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/cce/cache/pdrn1971f418.gif 1943], [http://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/cce/cache/pdrn1972f434.gif 1944], [http://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/cce/cache/pdrn1973f461.gif 1945].</ref> Ada Campbell Rose continued as editor until 1959.<ref>\"Ada Campbell Rose, Began Jack and Jill Magazine in '38\", ''[[The New York Times]]'', February 14, 1976, p. 28.</ref> The magazine began to accept outside advertising in 1962.<ref>Peter Bart, \"Advertising: Jack and Jill to Sell With Zeal\", ''The New York Times'', November 28, 1962, p. 61.</ref> Today the magazine is one of two children's magazines published by the U.S. Kids unit of ''[[Saturday Evening Post]]'' Society. In 2009, ''Jack and Jill'' merged with ''Children's Digest'', another kids magazine from the same publisher.\n\nJennifer Burnham edits ''Jack and Jill'' under the direction of Steven Slon. ''Jack and Jill'' is one of two children's publications in the U.S. Kids family of magazines, which are published by the Children's Better Health Institute,<ref name=jlt>{{cite journal|author=James L. Thomas|title=Magazines To Use With Children in Preschool and Primary Grades|journal=Young Children|date=November 1987|volume=43|issue=1|jstor=42725948}}</ref>  a division of the nonprofit The Saturday Evening Post Society. Its sister publication under the U.S. Kids banner is ''[[Humpty Dumpty Magazine]]'' (for children ages 2 to 6). The headquarters of ''Jack and Jill'' is in [[Indianapolis, Indiana]].<ref name=jlt/>\n\n==Features==\n*U.S. Kids Cover Contest: ''Jack and Jill'' holds an annual themed cover contest in which readers submit their artwork.<ref>[http://www.uskidsmags.com/artcontest/ U.S. Kids Art Contest Official Website]</ref> The winning entry is featured on the front cover, with second-, third-place, and Readers' Choice winners' art showcased inside the same issue. In addition, U.S. Kids also recognizes winners' art departments and teachers with cash awards to help support their programs. School art programs have been awarded more than $25,000 from the contest so far. Through this contest, U.S. Kids hopes to encourage young minds and those who teach them to continue creating wonderful art.\n*Reader-Created Content: ''Jack and Jill''<!-- -->'s editors strive to include as much kid-created content as possible, including their letters, personal essays, questions, photos, short poems, and artwork.\n*Nonfiction: Most of the nonfiction articles in ''Jack and Jill'' feature regular kids or groups of kids who are engaged in unusual, challenging, or interesting activities and serve as inspiration for readers.\n*Fiction: The fiction stories that appear in ''Jack and Jill'' are fun, engaging, and filled with humor. They provide kids with positive messages, such as self-reliance, being kind to others, and appreciating other cultures through modern characters.\n*Recipes: Each issue of the magazine includes a healthy, easy-to make recipe that kids can prepare themselves. The recipes promote healthy eating by incorporating fresh fruits and vegetables, whole grains, and muscle-building proteins.\n*Crafts: Each issue offers a new and unique age-appropriate craft that promotes the development of creativity.\n*Games/Puzzles: ''Jack and Jill'' magazine offers several pages of challenging puzzles and games in each issue, which promote problem-solving and independent thinking.\n\n==Notable contributors==\nAmerican author [[Pearl S. Buck]], winner of the 1932 [[Pulitzer Prize]] and the 1938 [[Nobel Prize in Literature]] for her novel ''[[The Good Earth]]'', contributed \u201cOne Bright Day,\u201d a two-part story that appeared in the August and September 1950 issues.\n\nCartoonist [[Ted Key]] contributed the two-page feature \"Diz and Liz\" from 1961 to 1972.\n\nChildren's author [[Ruth Plumly Thompson]] contributed the feature \"Perky Puppet\" from 1965 to 1970.\n\n[[Charles Ghigna]] (\u201cFather Goose\u201d), renowned poet and children's book author of 100 award-winning books and a Pulitzer Prize nominee for ''Returning to Earth'', served on ''Jack and Jill''<!-- -->'s editorial advisory board and has had his work published in the magazine.\n\nRenowned comic book writer [[Justin Gray]] contributed scripts for ''Jack and Jill''<!-- -->'s comics pages for several years.\n\nAcclaimed children's author [[David A. Adler]] has written a new Cam Jansen short story specifically for ''Jack and Jill'', which appeared in the Sep/Oct 2012 issue.\n\n''New York Times'' bestselling author [[Ben H. Winters]], author of ''The Secret Life of Ms. Finkleman'', ''The Mystery of the Missing Everything'', and ''[[Sense and Sensibility and Sea Monsters]]'', wrote an original short story for ''Jack and Jill'', which was published in the Nov/Dec 2012 issue.\n\n==Awards==\n*[[Parents' Choice Award]] Approved Winner, 2017\n*[[Parents' Choice Award]] Approved Winner, 2013\n*[[Parents' Choice Award]] Approved Winner, 2011\n*[[iParenting Media]] Awards Best Product Winner, 2009\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.uskidsmags.com/magazines/jack-and-jill}}\n\n{{Saturday Evening Post}}\n{{Cyrus Curtis}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jack And Jill (Magazine)}}\n[[Category:1938 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1938]]\n[[Category:American children's magazines]]\n[[Category:American bimonthly magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Philadelphia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox magazine\n| logo            = \n| logo_size       = \n| image_file      = Jack & Jill March 2008.jpg\n| image_size      = <!-- (defaults to user thumbnail size if no size is stated) -->\n| image_alt       = \n| image_caption   = March 2008 cover\n| editor          = \n| editor_title    = \n| previous_editor = \n| staff_writer    = \n| photographer    = \n| category        = Children's magazine\n| frequency       = Bimonthly\n| circulation     = \n| publisher       = \n| founder         = \n| founded         = \n| firstdate       = {{Start date|1938|month}} \n| company         = [[Saturday Evening Post]] Society\n| country         = United States\n| based           = [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]\n| language        = English\n| website         = {{URL|http://www.uskidsmags.com/magazines/jack-and-jill/}}\n| issn            = 0021-3829\n| oclc            = \n}}\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\n'''''Jack and Jill''''' is an [[United States|American]] [[bimonthly]] [[magazine]] for children 6 to 12 years old that takes its title from the [[nursery rhyme]] of [[Jack and Jill (nursery rhyme)|the same name]]. It features stories and educational activities.\n\nThe magazine features nonfiction articles, short stories, poems, games, comics, recipes, crafts, and more. Having been continuously produced for 80 years, it is one of the oldest American magazines for kids.\n\n==Mission==\nAs part of the Children's Better Health Institute\u2014a division of the Saturday Evening Post Society Inc., a 501 (c)(3) nonprofit charitable organization\u2014''Jack and Jill''<!-- -->'s mission is to promote the healthy physical, educational, creative, social, and emotional growth of children in a format that is engaging, stimulating, and entertaining for children ages 6 to 12.<ref>[http://www.uskidsmags.com/about/ U.S. Kids Magazines Official Website]</ref>\n\n==History==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Jack and Jill 1938.jpg|thumb|left|The first issue of ''Jack and Jill'' in 1938.]] -->\n''Jack and Jill'' magazine was launched by [[Curtis Publishing Company]] in 1938. It was the first addition to the Curtis line of magazines since it purchased ''[[Country Gentleman]]'' in 1911. The first editor of ''Jack and Jill'' was [[Ada Campbell Rose]] daughter-in-law of [[Philip Sheridan Rose]], the editor of ''Country Gentleman''.<ref>\"Jack and Jill\". ''Time''. Oct. 24, 1938.</ref> It was headquartered in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Wesley Francis Amar|title=Children's Magazines Today|journal=The Elementary English Review|date=November 1943|volume=20|issue=7|jstor=41382721}}</ref> The magazine's circulation grew to half a million before [[newsagent|newsstand]] sales (but not subscriptions) were suspended during [[World War II]] due to paper shortages. Newsstand sales returned in 1948.<ref>\"[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,853363,00.html Up the hill]\". ''Time'', November 8, 1948. U.S. copyright renewals:  [http://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/cce/cache/pdrn1969f396.gif 1941], [http://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/cce/cache/pdrn1970f412.gif 1942], [http://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/cce/cache/pdrn1971f418.gif 1943], [http://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/cce/cache/pdrn1972f434.gif 1944], [http://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/cce/cache/pdrn1973f461.gif 1945].</ref> Ada Campbell Rose continued as editor until 1959.<ref>\"Ada Campbell Rose, Began Jack and Jill Magazine in '38\", ''[[The New York Times]]'', February 14, 1976, p. 28.</ref> The magazine began to accept outside advertising in 1962.<ref>Peter Bart, \"Advertising: Jack and Jill to Sell With Zeal\", ''The New York Times'', November 28, 1962, p. 61.</ref> Today the magazine is one of two children's magazines published by the U.S. Kids unit of ''[[Saturday Evening Post]]'' Society. In 2009, ''Jack and Jill'' merged with ''Children's Digest'', another kids magazine from the same publisher.\n\nJennifer Burnham edits ''Jack and Jill'' under the direction of Steven Slon. ''Jack and Jill'' is one of two children's publications in the U.S. Kids family of magazines, which are published by the Children's Better Health Institute,<ref name=jlt>{{cite journal|author=James L. Thomas|title=Magazines To Use With Children in Preschool and Primary Grades|journal=Young Children|date=November 1987|volume=43|issue=1|jstor=42725948}}</ref>  a division of the nonprofit The Saturday Evening Post Society. Its sister publication under the U.S. Kids banner is ''[[Humpty Dumpty Magazine]]'' (for children ages 2 to 6). The headquarters of ''Jack and Jill'' is in [[Indianapolis, Indiana]].<ref name=jlt/>\n\n==Features==\n*U.S. Kids Cover Contest: ''Jack and Jill'' holds an annual themed cover contest in which readers submit their artwork.<ref>[http://www.uskidsmags.com/artcontest/ U.S. Kids Art Contest Official Website]</ref> The winning entry is featured on the front cover, with second-, third-place, and Readers' Choice winners' art showcased inside the same issue. In addition, U.S. Kids also recognizes winners' art departments and teachers with cash awards to help support their programs. School art programs have been awarded more than $25,000 from the contest so far. Through this contest, U.S. Kids hopes to encourage young minds and those who teach them to continue creating wonderful art.\n*Reader-Created Content: ''Jack and Jill''<!-- -->'s editors strive to include as much kid-created content as possible, including their letters, personal essays, questions, photos, short poems, and artwork.\n*Nonfiction: Most of the nonfiction articles in ''Jack and Jill'' feature regular kids or groups of kids who are engaged in unusual, challenging, or interesting activities and serve as inspiration for readers.\n*Fiction: The fiction stories that appear in ''Jack and Jill'' are fun, engaging, and filled with humor. They provide kids with positive messages, such as self-reliance, being kind to others, and appreciating other cultures through modern characters.\n*Recipes: Each issue of the magazine includes a healthy, easy-to make recipe that kids can prepare themselves. The recipes promote healthy eating by incorporating fresh fruits and vegetables, whole grains, and muscle-building proteins.\n*Crafts: Each issue offers a new and unique age-appropriate craft that promotes the development of creativity.\n*Games/Puzzles: ''Jack and Jill'' magazine offers several pages of challenging puzzles and games in each issue, which promote problem-solving and independent thinking.\n\n==Notable contributors==\nAmerican author [[Pearl S. Buck]], winner of the 1932 [[Pulitzer Prize]] and the 1938 [[Nobel Prize in Literature]] for her novel ''[[The Good Earth]]'', contributed \u201cOne Bright Day,\u201d a two-part story that appeared in the August and September 1950 issues.\n\nCartoonist [[Ted Key]] contributed the two-page feature \"Diz and Liz\" from 1961 to 1972.\n\nChildren's author [[Ruth Plumly Thompson]] contributed the feature \"Perky Puppet\" from 1965 to 1970.\n\n[[Charles Ghigna]] (\u201cFather Goose\u201d), renowned poet and children's book author of 100 award-winning books and a Pulitzer Prize nominee for ''Returning to Earth'', served on ''Jack and Jill''<!-- -->'s editorial advisory board and has had his work published in the magazine.\n\nRenowned comic book writer [[Justin Gray]] contributed scripts for ''Jack and Jill''<!-- -->'s comics pages for several years.\n\nAcclaimed children's author [[David A. Adler]] has written a new Cam Jansen short story specifically for ''Jack and Jill'', which appeared in the Sep/Oct 2012 issue.\n\n''New York Times'' bestselling author [[Ben H. Winters]], author of ''The Secret Life of Ms. Finkleman'', ''The Mystery of the Missing Everything'', and ''[[Sense and Sensibility and Sea Monsters]]'', wrote an original short story for ''Jack and Jill'', which was published in the Nov/Dec 2012 issue.\n\n==Awards==\n*[[Parents' Choice Award]] Approved Winner, 2017\n*[[Parents' Choice Award]] Approved Winner, 2013\n*[[Parents' Choice Award]] Approved Winner, 2011\n*[[iParenting Media]] Awards Best Product Winner, 2009\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.uskidsmags.com/magazines/jack-and-jill}}\n\n{{Saturday Evening Post}}\n{{Cyrus Curtis}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jack And Jill (Magazine)}}\n[[Category:1938 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1938]]\n[[Category:American children's magazines]]\n[[Category:American bimonthly magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Media in Philadelphia]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_and_Jill_(magazine)"}
{"title_page": "Cam Newton", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent addition of [[WP:INTREF|unsourced or poorly sourced content]]|small=yes}}\n{{other people}}\n{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name         = Cam Newton\n|image        = Cam newton 2016.jpg\n|image_size   = 250px\n|alt          =\n|caption      = Newton with the Carolina Panthers in 2016\n|current_team = Free agent\n|number       = \n|position     = [[Quarterback]]\n|birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1989|5|11|mf=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[Atlanta, Georgia]]\n|height_ft    = 6\n|height_in    = 5\n|weight_lbs   = 245\n|high_school  = [[Westlake High School (Georgia)|Westlake]] (Atlanta, Georgia)\n|college      = [[Florida Gators football|Florida]]<br/>[[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]]\n|draftyear    = 2011\n|draftround   = 1\n|draftpick    = [[List of first overall National Football League draft picks|1]]\n|pastteams    =\n* [[Carolina Panthers]] ({{NFL Year|2011}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2019}})\n|status       = \n|highlights   =\n* 3\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2012 Pro Bowl|2011]], [[2014 Pro Bowl|2013]], [[2016 Pro Bowl|2015]])\n* First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2015 All-Pro Team|2015]])\n* [[NFL Most Valuable Player]] (2015)\n* [[NFL Offensive Player of the Year]] (2015)\n* [[Bert Bell Award]] (2015)\n* [[National Football League Rookie of the Year Award|Pepsi NFL Rookie of the Year]] (2011) \n* [[National Football League Rookie of the Year Award|NFL Offensive Rookie of the Year]] (2011) \n* [[PFWA All-Rookie Team]] (2011)\n* 2\u00d7 [[BCS National Championship Game|BCS national champion]] ([[2009 BCS National Championship Game|2008]], [[2011 BCS National Championship Game|2010]]) \n* 2\u00d7 [[SEC Championship Game|SEC champion]] ([[2008 SEC Championship Game|2008]], [[2010 SEC Championship Game|2010]]) \n* [[Heisman Trophy]] (2010)\n* [[Maxwell Award]] (2010)\n* [[Walter Camp Award]] (2010)\n* [[Davey O'Brien Award]] (2010) \n* [[Associated Press College Football Player of the Year Award|AP College Player of the Year]] (2010)\n* [[Sporting News College Football Player of the Year|''Sporting News'' College Player of the Year]] (2010)\n* Consensus [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2010 College Football All-America Team|2010]]) \n* First-team All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] ([[2010 All-SEC football team|2010]])\n|statleague   = NFL\n|statweek     = \n|statseason   = 2019\n|statlabel1   = [[Touchdowns|TD]]\u2013[[Interceptions|INT]]\n|statvalue1   = 182\u2013108\n|statlabel2   = Passing yards\n|statvalue2   = 29,041\n|statlabel3   = Completion %\n|statvalue3   = 59.6\n|statlabel4   = [[Passer rating]]\n|statvalue4   = 86.1\n|statlabel5   = Rushing yards\n|statvalue5   = 4,806\n|statlabel6   = Rushing touchdowns\n|statvalue6   = 58\n|nfl          = NEW693984\n|pfr          =\n}}\n'''Cameron Jerrell Newton'''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blog.al.com/live/2010/11/best_cam_newton_headlines.html |title=Fodder: Best Cam Newton headlines |date=November 15, 2010 |website=AL.com |access-date=April 10, 2020 |quote=Cam Newton's middle name. It's Jerrell, by the way.}}</ref> (born May 11, 1989)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/N/NewtCa00.htm |title=Cam Newton Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]] who is a [[free agent]]. He played [[college football]] at [[Florida Gators football|Florida]] and [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]]. He was drafted as the [[List of first overall National Football League draft picks|first overall pick]] by the [[Carolina Panthers]] in the [[2011 NFL Draft]]. He was the 2011 NFL Rookie of the Year, is a three-time Pro Bowler, and was named the NFL MVP in 2015.\nIn his rookie year, Newton broke all-time NFL rookie records for passing and rushing yards. He became the first NFL quarterback to throw for 400 yards in his first game, shattering [[Peyton Manning]]'s first-game record by 120 yards. He also broke [[Otto Graham]]'s 61-year-old record for passing yards by any quarterback in an NFL debut.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/6962206/ron-rivera-says-cam-newton-carolina-panthers-exceeded-expectations |title=Ron Rivera praises Cam Newton |date=September 12, 2011 |access-date=September 14, 2011 |agency=Associated Press |website=ESPN.com}}</ref> Newton went on to become the first rookie quarterback to throw for 4,000 yards in a season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/tiny.cgi?id=EKdJi |title=NFL Rookie Season Passing Yards (as of 2011 NFL Season) |website=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]] |access-date=November 14, 2013}}</ref> He also ran for 14 touchdowns, more in a single season than any other quarterback in NFL history, breaking [[Steve Grogan]]'s 35-year-old record.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/tiny.cgi?id=43sbc |title=Rushing Touchdowns by an NFL Quarterback in a season |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=November 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nNewton capped off the 2015 season by capturing MVP honors and leading the Panthers to a 15\u20131 record and a trip to [[Super Bowl 50]]. Newton, along with [[Steve McNair]], [[Patrick Mahomes]], and [[Lamar Jackson]], is one of only four African-American quarterbacks to win AP NFL MVP.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theundefeated.com/features/mvp-patrick-mahomes-is-now-part-of-the-legendary-black-quarterback-fraternity/ |title=MVP Patrick Mahomes is now part of the legendary black quarterback fraternity |last=Rhoden |first=William C. |website=TheUndefeated.com |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{TOClimit|limit=3}}\n\n==High school career==\nNewton attended [[Westlake High School (Georgia)|Westlake High School]] in [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]], where he played for the Westlake Lions [[high school football]] team.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.fox5atlanta.com/news/carolina-panther-and-westlake-high-alum-cam-newton-super-bowl-bound |title=Carolina Panther and Westlake High Alum Cam Newton Super Bowl Bound |last=Dukes |first=Deidra |date=January 25, 2016 |work=WAGA |access-date=February 27, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> As a 16-year-old junior, he passed for 2,500 yards and 23 touchdowns and ran for 638 yards and nine touchdowns, gaining the attention of major college programs. In his senior year, Newton was rated a five-star prospect by [[Rivals.com]], the No. 2 [[Quarterback#Dual-threat quarterbacks|dual-threat quarterback]] in the nation, and the 14th quarterback and 28th player overall. He received scholarship offers from [[Florida Gators football|Florida]], [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]], [[Maryland Terrapins football|Maryland]], [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]], [[Mississippi State Bulldogs football|Mississippi State]], [[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma]], and [[Virginia Tech Hokies football|Virginia Tech]].<ref name=\"cameron\">{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/footballrecruiting/football/recruiting/player-Cameron-Newton-41356 |title=Cameron Newton |website=Yahoo! Sports |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130925014929/https://sports.yahoo.com/footballrecruiting/football/recruiting/player-Cameron-Newton-41356 |archive-date=September 25, 2013 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> He committed to the [[University of Florida]] at the beginning of his senior year, becoming part of the top-rated recruiting class in the country for 2007.<ref name=\"cameron\" />\n\n{{College athlete recruit start|40=yes|collapse=no|year=2007}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit  = Cameron Newton\n| position = QB\n| hometown = Atlanta, GA\n| highschool = Westlake HS\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 5\n| weight = 250\n| 40     = 4.51\n| commitdate = September 7, 2006\n| scout stars  = 4\n| rivals stars = 5\n| 247 stars    = 4\n| espn grade = 81\n}}\n{{College athlete recruit end\n| 40               =\n| year             = 2007\n| rivals ref title = Florida Football Commitments\n| scout ref title  = 2007 Florida Football Commits\n| espn ref title   = ESPN\n| rivals school    = florida\n| scout s          = 168\n| espn schoolid    = 57\n| scout overall    = 14 (QB)\n| rivals overall   = 2 (Dual-threat QB)\n| 247 overall      = 3 (Dual-threat QB)\n| espn overall     = 9 (QB)\n| accessdate       = November 6, 2013\n| bball            =\n}}\n\n==College career==\n\n===University of Florida===\n[[File:Gators2007QBs.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Newton, far left, with [[Dan Mullen]], [[John Brantley]], [[Tim Tebow]], and Bryan Waggener during his freshman season at Florida]]\n\nNewton initially attended the [[University of Florida]], where he was a member of the [[Florida Gators football]] team in [[2007 Florida Gators football team|2007]] and [[2008 Florida Gators football team|2008]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/cam-newton-1.html |title=Cam Newton College Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> As a freshman in 2007, Newton beat out fellow freshman quarterback [[John Brantley]] as the back-up for eventual [[Heisman Trophy]] winner [[Tim Tebow]]. He played in five games, passing for 40 yards on 5-of-10 and rushing 16 times for 103 yards and three touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/espn/eticket/story?page=camnewton |title=NFL draft 2011: Tracing Cam Newton's journey to the NFL |last=Merrill |first=Elizabeth |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=July 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/cam-newton-1/gamelog/2007/ |title=Cam Newton 2007 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> In 2008, during his sophomore season, Newton played in the season opener against [[2008 Hawaii Warriors football team|Hawaii]] but suffered an ankle injury and took a medical [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt season]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2008-08-30-florida.html |title=Hawaii at Florida Box Score, August 30, 2008 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Timanus |first=Eddie |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/college/football/sec/2010-10-21-newton-off-to-fast-start_N.htm |title=Auburn system suits quarterback Cam Newton well |date=October 22, 2010 |work=USA Today |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn November 21, 2008, Newton was arrested on felony charges of burglary, larceny, and obstruction of justice on an accusation that he stole a [[laptop|laptop computer]] from another University of Florida student. He was subsequently suspended from the team.<ref name=\"ArrestForPossession\">{{Cite news |url=http://blogs.orlandosentinel.com/sports_college_uf/2008/11/backup-qb-camer.html |title=Backup QB Cameron Newton arrested for possession of stolen property, suspended from team |last=Fowler |first=Jeremy |date=November 21, 2008 |work=Orlando Sentinel |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107181727/http://blogs.orlandosentinel.com/sports_college_uf/2008/11/backup-qb-camer.html |archive-date=January 7, 2009}}</ref> Campus police \"tracked the stolen laptop to the athlete...Newton tossed the computer out his dorm window in a humorously ill-advised attempt to hide it from cops.\"<ref name=\"TheSmokingGun\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/documents/college/cam-newton-lame-laptop-thief |title=Cam Newton, Lame Laptop Thief |date=November 9, 2010 |work=The Smoking Gun |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> All charges against Newton were dropped after he completed a court-approved pre-trial diversion program. \"I believe that a person should not be thought of as a bad person because of some senseless mistake that they made,\" said Newton in 2010. \"I think every person should have a second chance. If they blow that second chance, so be it for them.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.shreveporttimes.com/article/20101020/SPORTS0202/10200322/1001/SPORTS |title=Auburn's Cam Newton makes most of second chance |last=Gulbeau |first=Glenn |website=Shreveport Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101110195144/http://www.shreveporttimes.com/article/20101020/SPORTS0202/10200322/1001/SPORTS |archive-date=November 10, 2010 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Newton announced his intention to transfer from Florida three days before the Gators' [[2009 BCS National Championship Game|national championship]] win over [[2008 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma]]. In November 2010, Thayer Evans of [[Fox Sports]] reported that Newton faced potential expulsion from the University of Florida for three instances of academic dishonesty, prior to transferring.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://msn.foxsports.com/collegefootball/story/Source-says-Newton-left-Florida-after-cheating-scandal |title=Source: Newton left Florida after cheating scandal |last=Evans |first=Thayer |date=November 9, 2010 |publisher=Fox Sports |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110210141813/http://msn.foxsports.com/collegefootball/story/Source-says-Newton-left-Florida-after-cheating-scandal |archive-date=February 10, 2011 |access-date=February 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/10/sports/ncaafootball/10auburn.html |title=Newton Faced Suspension at Florida |last=Thamel |first=Pete |last2=Glier |first2=Ray |date=November 9, 2010 |website=New York Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523000720/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/10/sports/ncaafootball/10auburn.html |archive-date=May 23, 2013 |access-date=February 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Blinn College===\nIn January 2009, Newton transferred to [[Blinn College]] in [[Brenham, Texas]], to play for head coach [[Brad Franchione]], son of [[Dennis Franchione]]. That fall, he led his team to the 2009 [[NJCAA National Football Championship]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.morningsun.net/sports/x2072237174/Newton-leads-Blinn-to-title |title=Newton leads Blinn to title |last=Clark |first=Matthew |date=December 7, 2009 |website=Morning Sun |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213215735/https://www.morningsun.net/sports/x2072237174/Newton-leads-Blinn-to-title |archive-date=December 13, 2009}}</ref> throwing for 2,833 yards with 22 touchdowns and rushing for 655 yards.<ref name=\"schlabach draft\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/espn/eticket/story?page=camnewton |title=NFL draft 2011: Tracing Cam Newton's journey to the NFL |last=Schlabach |first=Mark |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=July 31, 2019}}</ref> He was named a [[Juco]] All-America honorable mention and was the most recruited Juco quarterback in the country.<ref name=\"schlabach draft\"></ref> Newton was ranked as the number one quarterback from either high school or junior college by [[Rivals.com]] and was the only five-star recruit.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/recruiting/player-Cameron-Newton-95471 |title=Cameron Newton |website=Yahoo! Sports |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131123005237/https://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/recruiting/player-Cameron-Newton-95471 |archive-date=November 23, 2013 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rivals100.rivals.com/viewrank.asp?SID=880&Year=2010&ra_key=2511 |title=Rivals.com Prospect Rankings |website=Rivals.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090911111455/http://rivals100.rivals.com/viewrank.asp?SID=880&Year=2010&ra_key=2511 |archive-date=September 11, 2009 |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> During Newton's recruitment, [[University of Oklahoma|Oklahoma]], [[Mississippi State University|Mississippi State]] and Auburn were his three finalists. He eventually signed with the [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn Tigers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/campusrivalry/post/2010/11/bob-stoops-on-recruiting-cam-newton-didnt-notice-anything/1 |title=Oklahoma coach Bob Stoops on recruiting Cam Newton: 'Didn't notice anything\" |last=Smith |first=Erick |date=September 11, 2010 |website=USA Today |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Auburn University===\nNewton started the first game of [[Auburn University]]'s 2010 season, a home win over [[2010 Arkansas State Red Wolves football team|Arkansas State]] on September 4, 2010. Newton accounted for five total offensive touchdowns and over 350 yards of total offense.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2010-09-04-auburn.html |title=Arkansas State at Auburn Box Score, September 4, 2010 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> He was named [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] Offensive Player of the Week following his performance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.auburntigers.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/090610aaa.html |title=Cameron Newton Named SEC Offensive Player Of The Week |date=September 6, 2010 |website=Auburn Tigers |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419010257/http://www.auburntigers.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/090610aaa.html |archive-date=April 19, 2012 |access-date=September 1, 2011}}</ref> Three weeks later, Newton had a second break-out game with five total touchdowns and over 330 total offensive yards against the [[2010 South Carolina Gamecocks football team|South Carolina Gamecocks]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/columns/story?columnist=maisel_ivan&id=5617732 |title=Cam Newton powers Auburn to 4\u20130 start |last=Maisel |first=Ivan |date=September 26, 2010 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn October 2, 2010, Newton led Auburn to a 52\u20133 victory over [[2010 Louisiana\u2013Monroe Warhawks football team|Louisiana-Monroe]]. He completed three touchdown passes, one of which went for 94 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2010-10-02-auburn.html |title=Louisiana-Monroe at Auburn Box Score, October 2, 2010 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> It was the longest touchdown pass and offensive play in Auburn football history. On October 9, 2010, Newton led Auburn to a 37\u201334 victory over [[2010 Kentucky Wildcats football team|Kentucky]]. He passed for 210 yards and rushed for 198 yards including 4 rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2010-10-09-kentucky.html |title=Auburn at Kentucky Box Score, October 9, 2010 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> On October 16, 2010, during the [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas]] game, Newton ran for three touchdowns and threw one touchdown pass.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/aub/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/101016-araustats.pdf |title=Scoring Summary (Final) Auburn Football No. 12 Arkansas vs No. 7 Auburn (Oct 16, 2010 at Auburn, AL) |website=CSTV.com |access-date=October 28, 2010}}</ref> Following these performances, media reports began to list Newton among the top 5 candidates to watch for the [[Heisman Trophy]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://heismanpundit.com/2010/10/12/the-heisman-pundit-heisman-poll-week-6/ |title=The Heisman Pundit Heisman Poll, Week 6 |date=October 12, 2010 |website=HeismanPundit.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101015211946/http://heismanpundit.com/2010/10/12/the-heisman-pundit-heisman-poll-week-6/ |archive-date=October 15, 2010 |access-date=July 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/campusrivalry/post/2010/11/heisman-watch-cam-newton-kellen-moore-lamichael-james/1 |title=Heisman Watch: Auburn's Cam Newton continues to lead |last=Smith |first=Erick |date=November 17, 2010 |website=USAToday.com |access-date=September 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cam Newton 2010-11-26.jpg|thumb|left|Newton (top) warming up prior to the 2010 [[Iron Bowl]]]]\nOn October 23, 2010, Newton led Auburn to a 24\u201317 victory over the [[LSU Tigers football|LSU Tigers]]. He rushed for 217 yards in the game, giving him 1,077 yards for the season, and set the SEC record for yards rushing in a season by a quarterback\u2014a record previously held by Auburn quarterback, Jimmy Sidle, that had stood for over 40 years. After this game, Newton became just the second quarterback to rush for over 1,000 yards in the conference's history.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2010-10-23-auburn.html |title=LSU at Auburn Box Score, October 23, 2010 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> He also broke [[Pat Sullivan (American football)|Pat Sullivan's]] school record for most touchdowns in a single season\u2014a record that had stood since 1971\u2014with 27. Both of these records were broken on the same play: a 49-yard touchdown run in which Newton escaped two tackles, corrected himself with his arm, eluded two additional tackles, and dragged a defender into the endzone for the touchdown. The play was described as Newton's \"Heisman moment\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/columns/story?columnist=forde_pat&id=5720792 |title=Cam Newton steps up against LSU |last=Forde |first=Pat |date=October 23, 2010 |website=[[ESPN.com]] |access-date=October 23, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://msn.foxsports.com/collegefootball/story/cam-newton-is-super-for-auburn-against-lsu-102310 |title=Cam Newton is super against LSU |last=Evans |first=Thayer |date=October 23, 2010 |website=[[Fox News Channel]] |access-date=October 25, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2010/10/cam_newton_has_a_heisman_momen.html |title=Cam Newton has a Heisman Moment |last=Scarbinsky |first=Kevin |date=October 23, 2010 |website=[[Birmingham News]] |publisher=Alabama Media Group |access-date=October 23, 2010}}</ref> Auburn received its first No. 1 overall [[Bowl Championship Series|BCS]] ranking, and Newton was listed as the overall favorite for the Heisman.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.scrippsnews.com/node/57418 |title=Heisman: Auburn's Cam Newton stays atop SHNS Heisman Poll |last=Lindsay |first=John |publisher=[[E. W. Scripps Company]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407064308/http://www.scrippsnews.com/node/57418 |archive-date=April 7, 2012 |access-date=October 28, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBy halftime of the game against [[2010 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]], Newton became the first SEC player to ever throw for 2,000 yards and rush for 1,000 yards in a single season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2010/11/halftime_stats_auburns_cam_new.html |title=Halftime stats: Auburn's Cam Newton becomes first SEC player to throw for 2,000 yards, run for 1,000 in a season |last=Goldberg |first=Charles |date=November 13, 2010 |website=Birmingham News |publisher=Alabama Media Group |access-date=November 13, 2010}}</ref> With the 49\u201331 victory, Auburn extended its winning streak to 11\u20130 and clinched the SEC West, allowing them to play in the SEC Championship game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2010-11-13-auburn.html |title=Georgia at Auburn Box Score, November 13, 2010 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> Newton led Auburn to a 28\u201327 victory over [[2010 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]] in the [[Iron Bowl]] after being down 24\u20130. The 24-point come-from-behind victory was the largest in [[Auburn Tigers football|the program's]] 117-year history. He passed for 216 yards with three passing touchdowns and ran for another.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2010-11-26-alabama.html |title=Auburn at Alabama Box Score, November 26, 2010 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Auburn offense 2010-11-26.jpg|thumb|Newton led Auburn back from a 24-point deficit to defeat rival Alabama.]]\nOn December 4, 2010, Newton led the Tigers to an SEC Championship, their first since 2004, by defeating South Carolina 56\u201317, setting an SEC Championship Game record for most points scored and largest margin of victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2010-12-04-auburn.html |title=South Carolina vs Auburn Box Score, December 4, 2010 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> Newton was named the game MVP after scoring a career-best six touchdowns (four passing and two rushing). With his performance, Newton also became the third player in [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|NCAA FBS]] history to throw and run for 20-plus touchdowns in a single season (along with former Florida teammate [[Tim Tebow]] and [[Colin Kaepernick]], who reached the milestone earlier the same day).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/columns/story?columnist=schlabach_mark&id=5885469 |title=Cam Newton puts stamp on title game |last=Schlabach |first=Mark |date=December 4, 2010 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=December 7, 2010}}</ref> Newton was named the 2010 SEC Offensive Player of the Year as well as the 2010 [[Associated Press College Football Player of the Year|AP Player of the Year]]. He was also one of four finalists for the 2010 [[Heisman Trophy]], which he won in a landslide victory.<ref name=\"finalist\">{{Cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=5892523 |title=Four finalists named for Heisman Trophy |date=December 6, 2010 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=December 7, 2010 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/campusrivalry/post/2010/12/cam-newton-wins-heisman/1 |title=Auburn quarterback Cam Newton captures Heisman Trophy |last=Smith |first=Erick |date=December 11, 2010 |work=USA Today |access-date=December 11, 2010}}</ref> He is the third Auburn player to win the [[Heisman Trophy]] (along with [[Pat Sullivan (American football)|Pat Sullivan]] and [[Bo Jackson]]).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/awards/heisman.html |title=Heisman Memorial Trophy Winners |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the victory in the SEC Championship, Auburn was invited to participate in the school's first [[2011 BCS National Championship Game|BCS National Championship Game]]. The game took place on January 10, 2011, in [[Glendale, Arizona]], with Auburn playing against the [[2010 Oregon Ducks football team|Oregon Ducks]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Russo |first=Ralph |url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2010/11/halftime_stats_auburns_cam_new.html |title=Auburn, Oregon give BCS title game new look |date=November 13, 2010 |access-date=December 5, 2010 |publisher=Alabama Media Group |agency=Associated Press |website=AL.com}}</ref> In a game that [[Steve Spurrier]] predicted to score as high as 60\u201355,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.footballscoop.com/news/3063-the-latest-from-mack-brown-rick-neuheisel-and-spurrier |title=Spurrier's Prediction |publisher=Football Scoop |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101208052046/http://www.footballscoop.com/news/3063-the-latest-from-mack-brown-rick-neuheisel-and-spurrier |archive-date=December 8, 2010}}</ref> Auburn beat Oregon just 22\u201319 to win the BCS National Championship. Newton threw for 262 yards, two touchdowns, and one interception. He also rushed 22 times for 65 yards, though he lost a fumble that later allowed Oregon to tie the game with limited time remaining. Once Auburn received the ball, Newton drove the Tigers down the field to win the game on Wes Byrum's last-second field goal. Media outlets wrote Newton was upstaged by teammate [[Michael Dyer]] (the game's Offensive MVP) and Auburn's defense, which held the high-powered Oregon ground game to just 75 yards<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nola.com/lsu/index.ssf/2011/01/well_remember_auburns_defense.html |title=We'll remember Auburn's defense prevailing \u2013 and those Oregon socks |last=Finney |first=Peter |date=January 12, 2011 |website=NOLA.com, The Times-Picayune |access-date=September 18, 2015}}</ref> On January 13, three days after winning the BCS National Championship, Newton declared for the [[2011 NFL Draft]], forgoing his senior season.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newsday.com/sports/college/college-football/auburn-s-newton-wins-heisman-in-landslide-1.2535321 |title=Auburn's Newton wins Heisman in landslide |last=Martin |first=Kimberly A. |date=December 11, 2010 |access-date=September 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n|+2010 Heisman Trophy Finalist Voting<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://auburntigers.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/121110aab.html |title=Cam Newton Wins Auburn's Third Heisman Trophy |date=December 11, 2010 |website=Auburn Tigers Athletics |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101214073234/http://auburntigers.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/121110aab.html |archive-date=December 14, 2010}}</ref>\n! Finalist\n! First place votes<br />(3 pts. each)\n! Second place votes<br />(2 pts. each)\n! Third place votes<br />(1 pt. each)\n! Total points\n|-\n| Cam Newton\n| 729\n| 24\n| 28\n| 2,263\n|-\n| [[Andrew Luck]]\n| 78\n| 309\n| 227\n| 1,079\n|-\n| [[LaMichael James]]\n| 22\n| 313\n| 224\n| 916\n|}\n\n====Eligibility controversy====\n[[File:Number2LSWho.JPG|thumb|right|Newton receiving a snap in 2010 against the [[LSU Tigers football|LSU Tigers]]]]\nNewton spent much of the second half of the 2010 football season embroiled in a controversy regarding allegations that his father, Cecil Newton, had sought substantial sums of money in return for his son playing for a major college football team, in violation of [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] rules.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2010/12/auburns_cam_newton_timeline_fr.html |title=Auburn's Cam Newton timeline: From recruitment to NCAA ruling |last=Goldberg |first=Charles |date=December 1, 2010 |publisher=Alabama Media Group |website=al.com}}</ref> In early November 2010, several [[Mississippi State University]] athletic [[Booster club|boosters]] reported to the media that, during their recruitment of his son out of [[Blinn College]] nearly a year earlier, Cecil Newton said that it would take \"more than just a scholarship\" to secure his son's services. This demand was communicated by booster and former Mississippi State football player Kenny Rogers to fellow boosters and former teammates Bill Bell and [[John Bond (quarterback)|John Bond]]. Rogers said in a [[Dallas]] radio interview that Cecil Newton said it would take \"anywhere between $100,000 and $180,000\" to get his son to transfer to Mississippi State.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=5792707 |title=Rogers: Cecil Newton put price on son |date=October 12, 2011 |publisher=ESPN}}</ref> Auburn maintained throughout the investigation, which had begun several months before the public was made aware of it,<ref name=\"cnid\">{{Cite news |url=http://i.usatoday.net/sports/college/football/2011-11-04-ncaa-auburn-newton.pdf |title=Cam Newton Investigation Documents |date=November 4, 2011 |publisher=usatoday.net}}</ref> that they were not involved in any pay-for-play scheme and that Cam Newton was fully eligible to play.\n\nOn November 30, Auburn declared Cam Newton ineligible after the NCAA found evidence that Cecil Newton solicited Mississippi State $120,000 to $180,000 in exchange for Cam Newton's athletic service, a violation of amateurism.<ref name=\"cnid\" /> Auburn immediately filed to have him reinstated on the basis that Kenny Rogers could not be considered an agent and that Cam Newton was not aware of his father's illegal activity.<ref name=\"cnid\" /> The NCAA almost immediately sided with Auburn and reinstated Newton the next day on December 1, declaring him eligible for the [[2010 SEC Championship Game]] three days later, stating that there was not sufficient evidence that Cam Newton or anyone from Auburn had any knowledge of Cecil Newton's actions.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://blogs.mercurynews.com/collegesports/2010/12/01/breaking-news-cam-newton-ruled-eligible-by-ncaa |title=Breaking news: Cam Newton ruled eligible by NCAA |date=December 1, 2010 |publisher=mercurynews.com.com}}</ref> Auburn subsequently limited the access Cecil Newton had to the program as result of NCAA findings. Also, due to increased pressure by the media and the NCAA investigation, Cecil Newton announced he would not attend the [[Heisman Trophy]] Ceremony.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2010/12/scarbinsky_cecil_newton_should.html |title=Scarbinsky: Cecil Newton should be barred from Heisman ceremony |last=Scarbinsky |first=Kevin |date=December 7, 2010 |publisher=Alabama Media Group |website=AL.com}}</ref> The NCAA reinstatement did not clear Cecil Newton of any wrongdoing; it did, however, establish Cam Newton's eligibility as a candidate for the Heisman Trophy, which he won in a landslide victory with 2,263 points and 729 first-place votes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.heisman.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/121310hsma.php |title=Cam Newton \u2013 2010 Heisman Winner |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007171709/http://www.heisman.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/121310hsma.php |archive-date=October 7, 2011 |publisher=Heisman.com}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2011, the NCAA officially closed its 13-month investigation into the recruitment of Cam Newton, unable to substantiate any allegation or speculation of illicit recruiting by Auburn,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://media.al.com/sports_impact/other/JJacobs_OC_101111_Auburn%28JAT%29.pdf |title=NCAA Letter To Jay Jacobs |date=October 12, 2011 |publisher=Alabama Media Group |website=al.com}}</ref><ref name=\"al\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2011/10/ncaa_says_auburn_finds_no_majo.html |title=NCAA says Auburn had no major violations, ends investigation in signing of quarterback Cam Newton |date=October 12, 2011 |publisher=Alabama Media Group |website=al.com}}</ref> and concluded that Cecil Newton only solicited a cash payment from Mississippi State and no other institution attempting to recruit his son.<ref name=\"cnid\" /> The investigation, which consisted of over 50 interviews and the reviewing of numerous bank records, IRS documents, telephone records, and e-mail messages, resulted in no findings that would indicate Auburn participated in any pay-for-play scenario in signing Cam Newton.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2011/10/ncaas_investigation_into_aubur.html |title=NCAA's investigation into Auburn, Cam Newton included review of bank records, IRS documents, phone records, emails |date=October 12, 2011 |publisher=Alabama Media Group |website=AL.com}}</ref><ref name=\"espn\">{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/7093495/ncaa-finds-no-major-violations-auburn-regarding-cam-newton |title=NCAA: No major violations for Auburn |date=October 12, 2011 |publisher=ESPN}}</ref> The NCAA said that the allegations failed to \"meet a burden of proof, which is a higher standard than rampant public speculation online and in the media\" and that the allegations were not \"based on credible and persuasive information\".<ref name=\"al\" /><ref name=\"espn\" /> The NCAA's Stacey Osburn said \"We've done all we can do. We've done all the interviews. We've looked into everything and there's nothing there. Unless something new comes to light that's credible and we need to look at, it's concluded.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/college/football/sec/story/2011-10-12/cam-newton-auburn-ncaa/50748074/1 |title=NCAA finds no major violations at Auburn in Cam Newton case |date=October 12, 2011 |website=USATODAY.com}}</ref>\n\n===College honors and awards===\n* [[Heisman Trophy]] (2010)\n* [[Maxwell Award]] (2010)\n* [[Walter Camp Award]] (2010)\n* [[Davey O'Brien Award]] (2010)\n* [[Manning Award]] (2010)\n* [[Associated Press College Football Player of the Year|AP College Football Player of the Year]] (2010)\n* Consensus first-team [[2010 College Football All-America Team|All-American]]; received first-team honors from [[American Football Coaches Association]], [[Associated Press]], ''[[The Sporting News]]'', [[Walter Camp Football Foundation]], [[CBS Sports]], ''[[College Football News]]'', [[ESPN]], [[Rivals.com]], [[Scout.com]] and ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' (2010)\n* First-team All-[[Southeastern Conference]] (2010)\n\n===College statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=2 | Year !! rowspan=2 | Team !! colspan=7 | Passing !! colspan=4 | Rushing\n|-\n! {{tooltip|Comp|Passes completed}} !! {{tooltip|Att|Passes attempted}} !! {{tooltip|Pct|Completion percentage}} !! {{tooltip|Yds|Passing yards}} !! {{tooltip|Y/A|Yards per passing attempt}} !! {{tooltip|TD|Passing touchdowns}} !! {{tooltip|Int|Interceptions}} !! {{tooltip|Att|Rushing attempts}} !! {{tooltip|Yds|Rushing yards}} !! {{tooltip|Avg|Yards per rushing attempt}} !! {{tooltip|TD|Rushing touchdowns}}\n|-\n| '''[[2007 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2007]]''' || [[2007 Florida Gators football team|Florida]] || 5 || 10 || 50.0% || 40 || 4.0 || 0 || 0 || 16 || 103 || 6.4 || 3\n|-\n| '''[[2008 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2008]]''' || [[2008 Florida Gators football team|Florida]] || 1 || 2 || 50.0% || 14 || 7.0 || 0 || 0 || 5 || 10 || 2.0 || 1\n|-\n| '''2009''' || [[Blinn College|Blinn]] || 204 || 336 || 60.7% || 2,833 || 8.4 || 22 || 5 || 108 || 655 || 6.1 || 16\n|-\n| '''[[2010 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2010]]''' || [[2010 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]] || 185 || 280 || 66.1% || 2,854 || 10.2 || 30 || 7 || 264 || 1,473 || 5.6 || 20\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| colspan=2 | '''Career''' || 395 || 628 || 62.9% || 5,741 || 9.1 || 52 || 12 || 393 || 2,241 || 5.7 || 40\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nIn late January 2011, Newton began working out with [[George Whitfield Jr.]] in San Diego.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/draft2011/news/story?id=6109802 |title=Cam Newton Works Out For Media |date=February 10, 2011 |publisher=ESPN}}</ref> Whitfield has worked with other quarterbacks such as [[Ben Roethlisberger]] and [[Akili Smith]]. On April 28, 2011, Newton was selected with the first overall pick in the 2011 NFL Draft by the Carolina Panthers.<ref>Associated Press (April 29, 2011). [http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/draft2011/news/story?id=6445107 Panthers make Cam Newton top pick]. ESPN.com. Retrieved September 16, 2011.</ref> He was the first reigning Heisman Trophy winner to go first overall since [[Carson Palmer]] in [[2003 NFL Draft|2003]]. He also was Auburn's fourth No. 1 selection after [[Tucker Frederickson]] ([[1965 NFL Draft|1965]]), [[Bo Jackson]] ([[1986 NFL Draft|1986]]), and [[Aundray Bruce]] ([[1988 NFL Draft|1988]]).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/draft-finder.cgi?request=1&year_min=1920&year_max=2017&draft_slot_min=1&draft_slot_max=1&pick_type=overall&pos%255B%255D=qb&pos%255B%255D=rb&pos%255B%255D=wr&pos%255B%255D=te&pos%255B%255D=e&pos%255B%255D=t&pos%255B%255D=g&pos%255B%255D=c&pos%255B%255D=ol&pos%255B%255D=dt&pos%255B%255D=de&pos%255B%255D=dl&pos%255B%255D=ilb&pos%255B%255D=olb&pos%255B%255D=lb&pos%255B%255D=cb&pos%255B%255D=s&pos%255B%255D=db&pos%255B%255D=k&pos%255B%255D=p&college_id=auburn&conference=any&show=all&order_by=default |title=Auburn No. 1 Overall Picks |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2011 NFL lockout, he spent up to 12 hours a day at the IMG Madden Football Academy in [[Bradenton, Florida]], spending up to two hours per day doing one-on-one training with fellow Heisman Trophy winner and ex-Panthers quarterback [[Chris Weinke]].<ref>[http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2011/05/13/cam-newton-working-daily-with-chris-weinke/ Cam Newton working daily with Chris Weinke | ProFootballTalk]. Profootballtalk.nbcsports.com. Retrieved on July 1, 2011.</ref>\n\nBefore the draft, Panthers owner [[Jerry Richardson]] asked Newton to maintain his clean-cut appearance after Newton told Richardson he had no tattoos or piercings and was thinking about growing his hair longer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/6894818/carolina-panthers-jerry-richardson-cam-newton-no-tats-piercings |title=Carolina Panthers' Jerry Richardson to Cam Newton \u2013 No tats, piercings \u2013 ESPN |date=August 25, 2011 |publisher=ESPN |access-date=September 4, 2012}}</ref> This gained some controversy on Richardson's part due to the fact that other players on the team didn't meet these guidelines. Dave Zirin, reporter for TheNation.com, even accused Richardson of racism.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/163011/jerry-richardson-cam-newton-and-color-control |title=Jerry Richardson, Cam Newton and the Color of Control |last=Dave Zirin |date=August 27, 2011 |website=The Nation |access-date=September 4, 2012}}</ref> Despite this, Newton agreed to Richardson's requests and was drafted first overall.\n\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 5\n|       weight = 248\n|         dash = 4.59\n|    ten split = 1.58\n| twenty split = 2.60\n|      shuttle = 4.18\n|   cone drill = 6.92\n|     vertical = 35\n|     broad ft = 10\n|     broad in = 6\n|        bench = N/A\n|    wonderlic = 21\n|     arm span = 33\u00be\n|    hand span = 9\u215e\n|         note = All values from 2011 [[NFL Scouting Combine]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=71142&draftyear=2011&genpos=QB |title=Cam Newton \u2013 QB \u2013 Auburn \u2013 2011 NFL Draft Scout Player Profile |access-date=May 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nflcombineresults.com/playerpage.php?i=6373 |title=Cam Newton \u2013 QB \u2013 Auburn \u2013 2011 NFL Combine Results |publisher=NFL Combine Results |access-date=May 11, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2011 season: Rookie season===\n[[File:Cam Newton during the 2011 NFL season.jpg|thumb|left|342x342px|Newton in his rookie season]]\nOn July 29, 2011, Newton signed a four-year contract, worth over $22&nbsp;million, with the [[Carolina Panthers]] that was fully guaranteed.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/6816915/top-pick-cam-newton-carolina-panthers-agree-four-year-22-million-dael |title=Cam Newton agrees to contract |last=Schefter |first=Adam |date=July 29, 2011 |access-date=July 29, 2011 |publisher=ESPN}}</ref> After unsuccessfully negotiating with quarterback [[Jimmy Clausen]] for the No. 2 jersey Newton wore at Auburn, he decided to keep the No. 1 jersey that the Panthers had assigned him after the draft.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://blogs.charlotte.com/panthers/2011/07/cam-newton-wearing-jersey-no-1-for-now.html |title=Cam Newton wearing jersey No. 1 \u2013 for now |last=Person |first=Joseph |date=July 26, 2011 |work=[[The Charlotte Observer]] |access-date=July 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2011/07/cam_newton_will_wear_no_1_in_c.html |title=Cam Newton will wear No. 1 in Carolina |publisher=al.com |access-date=September 4, 2012}}</ref> His quarterbacks coach was [[Mike Shula]], former head football coach of his college rival Alabama. A month later on September 1, 2011, he was named the Panthers' starting quarterback, ahead of [[Derek Anderson (American football)|Derek Anderson]] and Clausen.\n\nIn his NFL debut game on September 11, 2011, Newton was 24\u201337 passing for 422 yards, two touchdowns, and one interception, in a 28\u201321 road loss to the [[2011 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]]. With a quarterback rating of 110.4, he also rushed for a touchdown, and became the first rookie to throw for 400+ yards in his first career game. His 422 passing yards broke [[Peyton Manning]]'s rookie record for most passing yards on opening day.<ref>[http://scores.espn.go.com/nfl/boxscore?gameId=310911022 Carolina Panthers vs. Arizona Cardinals \u2013 Box Score]. ESPN.go.com (September 11, 2011). Retrieved on October 23, 2011.</ref>\n\nIn his second career game, a 30\u201323 home loss to the defending [[Super Bowl]] champion [[2011 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]], Newton broke his own record, set the weekend previously, with 432 yards passing, throwing and rushing for a touchdown.<ref>[http://espn.go.com/blog/statsinfo/post/_/id/26655/newton-sets-more-records-packers-get-win Newton sets more records, Packers get win]. ESPN.com. Retrieved September 18, 2011.</ref> Newton's 854 passing yards through the first two games of the season, the most in league history by a rookie,<ref name=\"Forbes432\">{{Cite news |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/topstories/2011-09-19-1634812073_x.htm |title=Newton throws for NFL rookie record 432 yards |date=September 19, 2011 |access-date=September 18, 2015 |agency=Associated Press |website=USAToday.com}}</ref> broke the NFL record of 827 set by [[Kurt Warner]] in the 2000 season and stood as the most by any quarterback in the first two weeks of the season until New England's [[Tom Brady]] broke the mark again later in the day with 940.<ref name=\"Forbes432\" /> He also became the only player to begin his career with consecutive 400-yard passing games<ref name=\"NewtonShows\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.theroot.com/buzz/cam-newton-shows-them-all |title=Cam Newton Shows Them All |last=Snyder |first=Deron |date=September 20, 2011 |website=TheRoot.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110921141659/http://www.theroot.com/buzz/cam-newton-shows-them-all |archive-date=September 21, 2011 |access-date=September 20, 2011 }}</ref> and broke the Carolina Panthers franchise record of 547 yards previously held by [[Steve Beuerlein]].<ref name=\"Cam2nd400\">{{Cite news |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=310918029 |title=Aaron Rodgers helps Packers overcome Cam Newton's 2nd straight 400-yard day |date=September 18, 2011 |access-date=September 18, 2011 |website=ESPN.go.com}}</ref> After Newton's second career game, Packers quarterback [[Aaron Rodgers]] commented, \"I think someone said in the locker room that I'm kind of glad we played him early in the season because when he figures it out fully, he's going to be even tougher to stop.\"<ref name=\"Cam2nd400\" /> Newton's three additional interceptions against the Packers tied him for the most interceptions thrown in the league. His total passing yards over the first three games was 1,012 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/pgl_finder.cgi?request=1&match=single&year_min=2011&year_max=2011&season_start=1&season_end=-1&pos=0&game_type=R&career_game_num_min=1&career_game_num_max=400&game_num_min=0&game_num_max=99&week_num_min=1&week_num_max=3&c1stat=pass_yds&c1comp=gt&c1val=1&c5val=1.0&order_by=pass_yds |title=2011 Passing Through Week 3 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Panthers recorded their first victory of the season against the [[2011 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]] 16\u201310. Newton threw for 158 yards and one touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201109250car.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Carolina Panthers \u2013 September 25th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> The Panthers played the [[Atlanta Falcons]], losing 31\u201317 while passing for 237 yards with no passing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201110160atl.htm |title=Carolina Panthers at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 October 16th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> Newton increased his team's record to 2\u20135 with a Week 7 win over the [[2011 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]] 33\u201320. He threw for 256 yards and one touchdown, completing 18 of his 23 passes. He also rushed for 59 yards and a touchdown, including one run for 25 yards. This performance brought Cam a passer rating of 127.5, his highest yet.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201110230car.htm |title=Washington Redskins at Carolina Panthers \u2013 October 23rd, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> With Carolina's win over the [[Indianapolis Colts]], Newton became the fourth rookie quarterback to pass for over 3,000 yards in his first season, joining Peyton Manning, [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]], and [[Sam Bradford]]. Newton set the NFL rushing touchdown record for quarterbacks on December 4, 2011, rushing for his 13th touchdown of the season in the fourth quarter against the [[2011 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]. The historic performance was part of a career-high three rushing touchdowns, which were part of a 38\u201319 win. In that game, he also caught a 27-yard pass from wide receiver [[Legedu Naanee]], making him a [[Triple-threat man|triple threat]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/gametracker/recap/NFL_20111204_CAR@TB |title=NFL Recap \u2013 Carolina Panthers at Tampa Bay Buccaneers \u2013 Dec 04, 2011 |date=December 4, 2011 |website=CBSSports.com |access-date=September 4, 2012}}</ref> On December 24, 2011, in a 48\u201316 victory over the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, Newton threw for 171 yards and three touchdowns and also rushed for 65 yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201112240car.htm |title=Tampa Bay Buccaneers at Carolina Panthers \u2013 December 24th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> In the process, he broke Peyton Manning's record of 3,739 yards passing for a rookie. On January 1, 2012 against the [[2011 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]], Newton threw for 158 yards and became the first rookie quarterback to throw for 4,000 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201201010nor.htm |title=Carolina Panthers at New Orleans Saints \u2013 January 1st, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> He finished his rookie season with 4,051 yards. Over the course of the season, when Newton had a turnover, the team was 0\u201310; when he had no turnovers, the team went 6\u20130.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/N/NewtCa00/gamelog/2011 |title=Cam Newton 2011 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn January 22, 2012, Newton was named to be heading to the Pro Bowl after the [[2011 New York Giants season|New York Giants]] beat the [[2011 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]] in the NFC Championship. Because [[Eli Manning]] was one of the three quarterbacks for the NFC to be selected, and with Newton being picked as the NFC alternate later in December, Newton was able to play in the Pro Bowl with Manning headed to the Super Bowl. He finished the Pro Bowl with 186 yards along with two touchdowns and three interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com/nfl/boxscore?id=6348 |title=NFC Nationals vs. AFC Americans \u2013 Box Score \u2013 January 29, 2012 |website=www.foxsports.com |language=en-US |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> Newton was named both [[AP Offensive Rookie of the Year]] and [[Pepsi NFL Rookie of the Year]] on February 4, 2012. He became the second straight number one pick to win the AP Rookie of the Year, after [[Sam Bradford]] won it the previous season. He was also the first Panther to win the Offensive award, but the second Panthers rookie of the year, following [[Julius Peppers]], the [[AP Defensive Rookie of the Year]] in 2002. Cam received his Offensive Rookie of the Year, and Pepsi NFL Rookie of the Year awards on the inaugural NFL Honors award show, with 47 of the 50 possible 50 AP votes (the other 3 going to [[Andy Dalton]]). He was named to the [[PFWA All-Rookie Team]], becoming the third Panthers quarterback to claim this award, joining [[Kerry Collins]] (1995) & [[Chris Weinke]] (2001). He also landed the number 5 and 2 play of the year with his 49-yard touchdown run against the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] (5), and his touchdown [[fumblerooski]] to Richie Brockel vs. the [[Houston Texans]].\nHe has the nickname Superman due to his touchdown celebration. Newton was rated as the 40th best player in the NFL by his peers on the NFL Top 100 player list.<ref name=\"AL.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2013/06/players_rank_cam_newton_46th_o.html |title=Players rank Cam Newton 46th on NFL's Top 100 Players of 2013 |website=AL.com |access-date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> His rookie season was when he started the Carolina Panther tradition \"Sunday Giveaway\", where the Panthers offensive players typically give away the football that they just scored a touchdown with to kids in the stands.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/carolina-panthers/post/_/id/18076/game-day-is-like-christmas-for-kids-who-get-td-footballs-from-cam-newton |title=Game day is like Christmas for kids who get TD footballs from Cam Newton |website=ESPN.com |access-date=March 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2012 season===\n[[File:Cam Newton Single.JPG|thumb|333x333px|Newton in 2012]]\nThe Panthers finished the season at 7\u20139.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/car/2012.htm |title=2012 Carolina Panthers Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> Though this season could be seen by some as a \"Sophomore Slump,\" he did improve in many statistical categories, improved on his efficiency, and cut back on his turnovers. Cam's noticeable decline in rushing touchdowns was due partially to the Panthers signing [[Mike Tolbert]] before the season began. Tolbert, a versatile fullback, was able to score goal line touchdowns as Cam had his rookie season. In Week 14, a 30\u201320 victory over the [[2012 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]], he had a career-high 116 rushing yards and a rushing touchdown to go along with 287 passing yards and two passing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201212090car.htm |title=Atlanta Falcons at Carolina Panthers \u2013 December 9th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> He finished his second professional season with 3,869 passing yards, 19 passing touchdowns, 12 interceptions, 741 rushing yards, and eight rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/N/NewtCa00/gamelog/2012 |title=Cam Newton 2012 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> Newton also led the league in Yards Per Completion (13.8)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/N/NewtCa00.htm |title=Cam Newton |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> and was tied for second with [[Peyton Manning]] in Yards Per Attempt (8.0) behind Robert Griffin III.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2012/passing.htm |title=2012 NFL Passing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> Newton was rated as the 46th best player by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2013]] list.<ref name=\"AL.com\" />\n\n===2013 season: first playoff appearance===\n[[File:Cam Newton 2014 Pro Bowl.png|thumb|upright|Newton in [[2014 Pro Bowl]].]]\nThe 2013 season turned out to be a success, with Newton leading his team to a 12\u20134 record and a first round bye in the playoffs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2013/ |title=2013 NFL Standings & Team Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> In the regular season, he recorded 3,379 passing yards, 24 touchdowns, 13 interceptions, 585 rushing yards, and six rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/N/NewtCa00/gamelog/2013 |title=Cam Newton 2013 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/car/2013.htm |title=2013 Carolina Panthers Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> Newton was selected for the 2014 Pro Bowl. The week after, he lost his first NFL playoff game to the [[2013 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]] in the [[2013\u201314 NFL playoffs#NFC: San Francisco 49ers 23, Carolina Panthers 10|Divisional Round]]. In the 23\u201310 loss, he had 267 passing yards, one touchdown, and two interceptions to go along with 54 rushing yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201401120car.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 San Francisco 49ers at Carolina Panthers \u2013 January 12th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/statistics/player/_/stat/passing/sort/quarterbackRating |title=2014 NFL Player Passing Stats \u2013 National Football League \u2013 ESPN |website=ESPN.com |access-date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> Newton was drafted third in the first annual Pro Bowl Draft, by Team Sanders. Newton played the second and third quarter, and rushed for a touchdown. Newton was rated as the 24th best player on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2014]] list.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.charlotte.com/panthers/2014/06/cam-newton-top-25-nfl-network-list-top-100-players-panthers-nfl.html |title=Inside the Panthers |website=charlotte.com |access-date=December 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2014 season: injury-plagued season===\n[[File:Cam Newton 2014.jpg|thumb|upright|Newton in 2014.]]\nOn March 21, 2014, Newton underwent surgery to \"tighten\" up his ankle ligaments, which Newton admitted he had dealt with since his college days at [[Auburn University]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000336283/article/rivera-cam-newtons-ankle-injury-likely-from-auburn |title=Rivera: Cam Newton's ankle injury likely from Auburn |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> The estimated recovery time was four months, which caused him to miss [[Training camp (National Football League)|training camp]] and the first preseason game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2000678-breaking-down-cam-newtons-ankle-injury-and-surgery |title=Breaking Down Cam Newton's Ankle Injury and Surgery |last=Siebert |first=Dave |website=Bleacher Report |access-date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> During the third preseason game against the [[2014 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], Newton suffered a hairline fracture on his ribs after a hit from [[Jamie Collins (American football)|Jamie Collins]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nesn.com/2014/08/jamie-collins-broke-cam-newtons-rib-in-patriots-panthers-preseason-game-gif/ |title=Jamie Collins Broke Cam Newton\u2019s Rib In Patriots-Panthers Preseason Game (GIF) \u2013 New England Patriots |website=NESN.com |access-date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> Newton's streak of starting 48 consecutive games was snapped during the Panthers opening game 20\u201314 victory over the [[2014 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.charlotte.com/panthers/2014/09/cam-newton-inactive-vs-bucs.html |title=Inside the Panthers |website=charlotte.com |access-date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> Newton made his debut during Carolina Panthers home opener against the [[2014 Detroit Lions season|Detroit Lions]] in Week 2. He recorded 300 yards of offense with a touchdown, no turnovers, and a 100.2 quarterback rating en route to a 24\u20137 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/is-cam-newton-nfl-s-most-underrated-qb--183822672-nfl.html |title=Is Cam Newton NFL's most underrated QB? |date=September 15, 2014 |website=Yahoo Sports |access-date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> Through his first three starts in the season, Newton recorded a 110.8 quarterback rating against the blitz.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.profootballfocus.com/blog/2014/10/03/pff-preview-bears-panthers-week-5/ |title=PFF Preview: Bears @ Panthers, Week 5 |last=Stevens |first=AJ |date=October 3, 2014 |website=Pro Football Focus |access-date=September 17, 2015}}</ref> During the Panthers Week 5 victory against the [[2014 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]], Newton led the Panthers from a 14-point deficit and was named to the [[Pro Football Focus]] (PFF) Team of the Week for his performance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.profootballfocus.com/blog/2014/10/06/all-star-team-of-the-week-week-5/ |title=All-Star Team of the Week: Week 5 |last=McGuinness |first=Gordon |date=October 3, 2014 |website=Pro Football Focus |access-date=September 17, 2015}}</ref> Senior producer of NFL Films [[Greg Cosell]] and respected Football Outsiders columnist and Pre Snap Reads owner, Cian Fahey, both noted Newton's clear development and growth as a pocket passer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nfl-shutdown-corner/greg-cosell-s-week-5-analysis--cam-newton-s-improvement-is-clear-175643535.html |title=Greg Cosell's Week 5 analysis: Cam Newton's improvement is clear |date=October 7, 2014 |website=Yahoo Sports |access-date=December 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.footballoutsiders.com/film-room/2014/film-room-cam-newton |title=Film Room: Cam Newton |last=Fahey |first=Cian |date=January 1, 2015 |website=FootballOutsiders.com |access-date=September 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2476588-cam-newtons-development-has-made-him-worth-massive-contract |title=Cam Newton's Development Has Made Him Worth Massive Contract |last=Fahey |first=Cian |date=May 26, 2015 |website=BleacherReport.com |access-date=September 17, 2015}}</ref> During the Panthers Week 6 37\u201337 tie against the [[2014 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]], Newton accounted for 91% of the offense, recording a career-high 29 of 46 completions for 286 yards with two touchdowns and an interception along with 17 rushing attempts for 107 yards and a rushing touchdown, the most since the 2012 Week 14 win against Atlanta, when he had 116 on nine carries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201410120cin.htm |title=Carolina Panthers at Cincinnati Bengals \u2013 October 12th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2014/10/12/5238123/carolina-panthers-quarterback.html |title=Carolina Panthers quarterback Cam Newton finally looks the part |last=Jones |first=Jonathan |date=October 12, 2014 |access-date=September 17, 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101013205/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2014/10/12/5238123/carolina-panthers-quarterback.html |archive-date=January 1, 2015 |website=Charlotte Observer}}</ref> Through the first six games in the season, Newton averaged 2.53 seconds to attempt a pass (2.73 in 2013) and has had the ball out in under 2.5 seconds on 51.8% of his drop-backs (40% in 2013).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.profootballfocus.com/blog/2014/10/17/pff-preview-panthers-packers-week-7/ |title=PFF Preview: Panthers @ Packers, Week 7 |last=Phillips |first=Chris |date=October 17, 2014 |access-date=September 17, 2015}}</ref> Newton had arguably his best game of the season in a 41\u201310 victory over the [[2014 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]]. Newton completed 21\u201333 passes for 226 yards and three touchdowns. Along with that he had 83 rushing yards and one rushing touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201412070nor.htm |title=Carolina Panthers at New Orleans Saints \u2013 December 7th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> He was named NFC Offensive Player of the Week for his efforts in that game and with this performance, Newton has had four games with at least 200 passing yards and 80 rushing yards with multiple touchdown passes and a rushing touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2014/week_14.htm |title=2014 NFL Week 14 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> That is the most such games in NFL history.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://proplayerinsiders.com/nfl-player-team-news-features/cam-newton-named-nfc-offensive-player-week/ |title=Cam Newton Named NFC Offensive Player of Week |date=December 10, 2014 |website=ProPlayerInsiders.com |access-date=September 17, 2015}}</ref> Two days following the Saints game, Newton was involved in a well-publicized car crash in which he fractured two vertebrae in his lower back. He missed only one game and returned to the field a week later in a match against the Cleveland Browns to make the final end-of-season push to win the NFC South division and once again make the playoffs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2014 |title=2014 NFL Standings & Team Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nNewton led the Carolina Panthers to the first back-to-back division titles in the NFC South since the formation of the division and became the first quarterback since [[Michael Vick]] and [[Randall Cunningham]] as the only quarterbacks in NFL history with four seasons with at least 500 rushing yards.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/12/28/fbn-panthers-falcons-recap-idUSMTZEACTBIO0CU20141228 |title=Panthers 34, Falcons 3 |date=December 28, 2014 |access-date=September 17, 2015 |website=Reuters.com}}</ref> During the season, Newton also tied [[John Elway]], [[Otto Graham]], and [[Y. A. Tittle]] for 10th all time in rushing touchdowns by a quarterback with 33.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://fantasynews.cbssports.com/fantasyfootball/update/24920414/panthers-cam-newton-finds-paydirt-twice-to-take-nfc-south-crown |title=Panthers' Cam Newton finds paydirt twice to take NFC South crown |last=Mello |first=Igor |date=December 28, 2014 |access-date=September 17, 2015 |website=CBSSports.com}}</ref> Further, with his four victories in December, Newton ranked second in the NFL in December wins over the past four years with 14 only behind [[Tom Brady]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thestate.com/2014/12/26/3894815_pnthers-tweets-before-panthers.html |title=Panthers' Tweets |date=December 26, 2014 |website=TheState.com}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Newton's 33 rushing touchdowns were the most by a quarterback in his first four seasons. He is also the only player in NFL history to have 10,000 passing yards and 2,000 rushing yards in his first four seasons and the first to have at least 3,000 passing yards and 500 rushing yards in four consecutive seasons.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blackandbluereview.com/cam-newton-first-four-seasons/ |title=On Cam Newton\u2019s Birthday, a Look at His First Four Seasons |last=Voth |first=Bill |date=May 11, 2015 |website=blackandbluereview.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518082724/http://blackandbluereview.com/cam-newton-first-four-seasons/ |archive-date=May 18, 2015 |access-date=September 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe following week, Newton led the Panthers to their first playoff win in nine years in the [[2014\u201315 NFL playoffs#NFC: Carolina Panthers 27, Arizona Cardinals 16|Wild Card Round]] over the [[2014 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]], throwing for 198 yards and two touchdowns while running for 35 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/gamelog/_/id/13994/cam-newton |title=Cam Newton Game-by-Game Stats |publisher=ESPN}}</ref> Newton and the Panthers were defeated by the [[2014 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]] 31\u201317 in the [[2014\u201315 NFL playoffs#NFC: Seattle Seahawks 31, Carolina Panthers 17|Divisional Round]]. Newton was 23\u201336 for 245 yards with two touchdowns, two interceptions, and 37 rushing yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201501100sea.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Carolina Panthers at Seattle Seahawks \u2013 January 10th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> Despite missing two games and dealing with ankle, rib, throwing hand, and back injuries through the entire season, Newton was rated as the 73rd best player in the NFL on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2015|NFL Top 100 player list]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blackandbluereview.com/cam-newton-top-100-players-2015/ |title=Cam Newton Drops to No. 73 on \u2018Top 100 Players\u2019 List |last=Voth |first=Bill |date=May 20, 2015 |website=blackandbluereview.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529161844/http://blackandbluereview.com/cam-newton-top-100-players-2015/ |archive-date=May 29, 2015 |access-date=September 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2015 season: MVP season and Super Bowl 50 appearance===\n[[File:Saints vs Panthers 12.6.15 070.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Newton playing against the [[2015 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]] in [[2015 Carolina Panthers season|2015]].]]\nOn June 2, 2015, the Panthers and Newton agreed to a five-year, $103.8&nbsp;million contract extension.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000495161/article/cam-newton-panthers-reach-1038m-extension |title=Cam Newton, Panthers reach $103.8M extension |last=Wesseling |first=Chris |date=June 2, 2015 |publisher=NFL.com |access-date=June 2, 2015}}</ref> Through the 2015 preseason, Newton graded as [[Pro Football Focus|PFF's]] best quarterback.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/PFF_Sam/status/640212121805017089 |title=Sam Monson |website=Twitter |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> During the season-opener against the [[2015 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]], Newton finished with 175 yards passing, one touchdown, and one interception, while rushing for 35 yards. This was the first NFL opening-day victory for Newton (the Panthers won their opener in 2014 with an injured Newton on the sidelines).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/spt-columns-blogs/scott-fowler/article35150676.html#storylink=cpy |title=Carolina Panthers grab an ugly win against Jacksonville in season opener |website=charlotteobserver |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> During the Panthers' Week 2 victory over the [[2015 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]], Newton finished with 195 yards passing, two passing touchdowns, and one interception, while rushing for 76 yards and one touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509200car.htm |title=Houston Texans at Carolina Panthers \u2013 September 20th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> In week three against the [[2015 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]], Newton passed for 315 yards and two passing touchdowns to go along with a rushing touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509270car.htm |title=New Orleans Saints at Carolina Panthers \u2013 September 27th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> It marked the 26th game in Newton's career in which he had a passing and a rushing touchdown, ranking second all-time in NFL history behind only [[Steve Young]] (31).<ref name=\"passing TD and rushing TD\">{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/21Rx5 |title=Passing TD and rushing TD |website=pro-football-reference.com |access-date=September 29, 2015}}</ref> Further, it marked the 14th time in his career where Newton notched two-plus touchdown passes and at least one rushing touchdown, third-most in the NFL since 1960, behind only [[Steve Young]] (17) and [[Fran Tarkenton]] (16).<ref name=\"nfl.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000542798/article/cam-newton-pushing-panthers-with-mvpcaliber-performance |title=Cam Newton pushing Panthers with MVP-caliber performance |website=NFL.com |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> Through the first three games of the season, Newton accounted for 76% of the total offensive yards and 88% of the total touchdowns the Panthers generated.<ref name=\"nfl.com\" /> Newton helped lead the Panthers to a 3\u20130 start, the first time they had done so since the [[2003 NFL Season]]. Several experts noted Newton's continued growth as a quarterback; [[Gil Brandt]] noted Newton's improving internal clock in the pocket, citing his career low sack percentage of 4.8% in the early season;<ref name=\"nfl.com\" /> senior NFL columnist for CBSSports.com, Pete Prisco, noting Cam's improved pocket patience, mechanics, and ability to read defenses;<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/writer/pete-prisco/25323979/after-further-review-how-cam-newton-is-growing-into-a-complete-qb |title=After Further Review: How Cam Newton is growing into a complete QB |website=CBSSports.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004022113/http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/writer/pete-prisco/25323979/after-further-review-how-cam-newton-is-growing-into-a-complete-qb |archive-date=October 4, 2015 |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> Cian Fahey noted Newton's development into a refined pocket passer with the athleticism to diversify any offense with a multidimensional run game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.footballoutsiders.com/film-room/2015/film-room-cam-newton-0 |title=FOOTBALL OUTSIDERS: Innovative Statistics, Intelligent Analysis \u2013 Film Room: Cam Newton |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> In the following week, during a 37\u201323 victory over the [[2015 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], Newton went 11 of 22 passing for 124 yards and two touchdowns while leading the team in rushing with 51 yards to give the Panthers a 4\u20130 record for the first time since 2003.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/carolina-panthers-tampa-bay-buccaneers-20151004027/ |title=Carolina at Tampa Bay \u2013 2015-10-04 \u2013 National Football League \u2013 Yahoo! Sports |website=Yahoo Sports |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> As a rusher, through the first four weeks, Newton ranked 3rd in the NFL in rushes for first downs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/statistics/player/_/stat/rushing/sort/rushingFirstDowns |title=2015 NFL Player Rushing Stats \u2013 National Football League \u2013 ESPN |website=ESPN.com |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a Week 4 bye, Newton threw for 269 yards, two interceptions, and a touchdown and rushed for 30 yards and a touchdown while leading the Panthers to victory against the [[2015 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]]. It marked just the 3rd home Seahawks loss in the [[Russell Wilson]] era.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nfl-shutdown-corner/seahawks-now-in-last-place-after-blowing-another-big-fourth-quarter-lead-001511269.html |title=Seahawks in last place after blowing another big fourth-quarter lead |date=October 19, 2015 |website=Yahoo Sports |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> It also marked the first franchise win in Seattle and Newton's ninth career fourth-quarter comeback win.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blackandbluereview.com/rapid-reactions-panthers-seahawks-week-6/ |title=Rapid Reactions: Panthers Finally Beat Seahawks |website=Black and Blue Review |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> During the game, Newton also recorded the 36th career rushing touchdown of his career; over that span, only [[Marshawn Lynch]] and [[Adrian Peterson]] were the only players to record more rushing touchdowns since 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/ESPNStatsInfo/status/657587806324166656 |title=ESPN Stats & Info on Twitter |website=Twitter |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> Through the first five weeks of the season, Newton recorded a career-high 67.6% of passes under pressure.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/ChrisTrapasso/status/656603948233560065 |title=Chris Trapasso |website=Twitter |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> The following week against the [[2015 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], Newton led the Panthers to a victory, earning the Panthers their first 6\u20130 record in franchise history; during the game, he threw three interceptions and recorded his 28th game with a rushing touchdown and a passing touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nfl-shutdown-corner/panthers-remain-undefeated--slog-past-eagles-in-a-lumpy-game-041609163.html |title=Panthers remain undefeated, slog past Eagles in a lumpy game |date=October 26, 2015 |website=Yahoo Sports |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> In Week 8, against the [[2015 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], Newton threw for 248 yards, two touchdowns, and one interception, as the Panthers moved to 7\u20130 with a 29\u201326 overtime victory;<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201511020car.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at Carolina Panthers \u2013 November 2nd, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> with the win, Newton became the first quarterback in NFL history to earn a comeback victory with his team trailing in overtime.<ref name=\"footballoutsiders.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.footballoutsiders.com/clutch-encounters/2015/clutch-encounters-week-8 |title=FOOTBALL OUTSIDERS: Innovative Statistics, Intelligent Analysis \u2013 Clutch Encounters: Week 8 |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe following week, Newton led the Panthers to their first 8\u20130 start in franchise history with a 37\u201329 victory over the [[2015 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]]; Newton went 15\u201330 for 297 yards passing, three touchdowns, and one interception to go along with 9 rush, 57 yards, and one touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/green-bay-packers-carolina-panthers-20151108029/ |title=Green Bay at Carolina \u2013 2015-11-08 \u2013 National Football League \u2013 Yahoo! Sports |website=Yahoo Sports |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> Further, for the first time in his career, Newton threw for 200 yards and three touchdowns in a single half.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2587397-packers-vs-panthers-carolina-grades-notes-and-quotes/page/3 |title=Packers vs. Panthers: Carolina Grades, Notes and Quotes |last=Bryan Knowles |website=Bleacher Report |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> For his game against the Packers, Newton was named the NFC Offensive Player of the Week.<ref name=\"charlotteobserver.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/nfl/carolina-panthers/nfl-blog/article44238120.html |title=Cam Newton wins NFC Offensive Player of the Week award |website=charlotteobserver |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> The following week, during the Panthers 27\u201310 victory over the [[2015 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]], Newton went 21 for 26 passes for 217 yards and 1 passing touchdown while recording 9 rushes for 23 yards and 1 rushing touchdown. Newton began the game with 11 straight completions, tying his career best in a single game (vs. Bucs on 11/18/12).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blackandbluereview.com/panthers-at-titans-stats-and-superlatives/ |title=Panthers at Titans: Stats and Superlatives |website=Black and Blue Review |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129221056/http://blackandbluereview.com/panthers-at-titans-stats-and-superlatives/ |archive-date=January 29, 2016 |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> The following week, Newton led the Panthers to a 44\u201316 victory over the [[2015 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]]. During the game, Newton threw for a career-high five touchdown passes and became the only quarterback in NFL history with 100+ passing touchdowns and 25+ rushing touchdowns in his first five seasons.<ref name=\"twitter.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/RLiuNFL/status/668557274172919808 |title=Randall Liu |website=Twitter |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> For his efforts, Newton was named the NFC Offensive Player of the Week for the second time this season.<ref name=\"panthers.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.panthers.com/news/article-2/Cam-Newton-named-NFC-Offensive-Player-of-the-Week/a600635d-20c4-408f-9045-a3ac2cdfe1c3 |title=Cam Newton named NFC Offensive Player of the Week |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130013709/http://www.panthers.com/news/article-2/Cam-Newton-named-NFC-Offensive-Player-of-the-Week/a600635d-20c4-408f-9045-a3ac2cdfe1c3 |archive-date=January 30, 2016 |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> During the Panthers 33\u201314 victory over the [[2015 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]] on Thanksgiving, Newton completed 16-of-27 passes for 183 yards, including going 8-of-16 on third downs, and rushed 12 times for 45 yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000588912/article/dominant-panthers-prove-theyre-worthy-of-160-talk |title=Dominant Panthers prove they're worthy of 16\u20130 talk |website=NFL.com |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> During the Panthers 41\u201338 victory over the [[2015 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]], Newton finished with 380 combined passing and rushing yards and five touchdown passes. He was 10 of 14 for 154 yards, two touchdowns and a 147 QB Rating under pressure. He also led the game-winning 75-yard touchdown drive to the Panthers undefeated through their first 12 games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.profootballfocus.com/blog/2015/12/07/car-no-grades-panthers-fend-off-saints-remain-undefeated/ |title=CAR-NO Grades: Panthers fend off Saints, remain undefeated |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> For his performance, Newton was named NFC Offensive Player of the week for the third time in five weeks. The last time a player achieved that feat was 2007, when [[Tom Brady]] of the [[New England Patriots]] won three player of the week awards in five weeks while quarterbacking the New England Patriots during an undefeated regular season.<ref name=\"profootballtalk.nbcsports.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/12/09/newton-wins-another-nfc-offensive-player-of-the-week-award/#comments |title=Newton wins another NFC Offensive Player of the Week award \u2013 ProFootballTalk |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> The following week, during the Panthers 38\u20130 victory over the [[2015 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]], Newton completed 15 of 21 passes for 265 yards, 3 passing touchdowns, and finished with a career-high quarterback rating of 153.3.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.denverpost.com/broncos/ci_29245934/cam-newton-panthers-pound-falcons-38-0-clinch |title=Cam Newton, Panthers pound Falcons 38\u20130, clinch 1st-round bye |last=Reed |first=Steve |date=December 13, 2015 |work=[[The Denver Post]] |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> The Panthers amassed 225 yards of offense in just the first quarter of the game; a franchise record. During the Panthers thrilling 38\u201335 victory against the [[2015 New York Giants season|New York Giants]], Newton went 25 of 45 for 340 yards and 5 passing touchdowns while adding 8 rushes for 100 yards, his third career game with at least 100 rushing yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201512200nyg.htm |title=Carolina Panthers at New York Giants \u2013 December 20th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> Newton also led the Panthers on his 12th-ever game-winning drive, and his fourth of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2601081-panthers-vs-giants-carolina-grades-notes-and-quotes/page/2 |title=Panthers vs. Giants: Carolina Grades, Notes and Quotes |last=Knowles |first=Bryan |date=December 20, 2015 |website=[[Bleacher Report]] |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> For his efforts, Newton was again named the NFC Offensive Player of the Week. Newton became the NFL's first player to win the award four times in a seven-week span since San Diego's [[LaDainian Tomlinson]] in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blackandbluereview.com/stats-and-superlatives-cam-newtons-4th-player-of-the-week-award/ |title=Stats and Superlatives: Newton's 4th Player of the Week Award |website=Black and Blue Review |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304072919/http://blackandbluereview.com/stats-and-superlatives-cam-newtons-4th-player-of-the-week-award/ |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThrough the first 15 weeks of the NFL season, Newton led the Panthers to a 14\u20130 record. During that span, he also threw the second-most touchdown passes and led the NFL with 40 combined passing and rushing touchdowns. Newton was on the field for 660 of Carolina's 923 plays in which he was either the decision-maker or ball carrier after the snap, which accounted for 72 percent of the Panthers' total snaps. Further, Newton had the second-lowest percentage of passing yards gained after the catch among NFL quarterbacks and 40 of Carolina's 49 touchdowns this season were either thrown or run by Newton.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/arizona-cardinals/post/_/id/18368/cam-newton-pulling-away-from-mvp-pack |title=MVP Watch: Cam Newton pulling away from pack |website=ESPN.com |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Panthers had their first setback in the 20\u201313 away loss to the Atlanta Falcons in their second divisional matchup. In the loss, Newton was 17 of 30 for 142 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201512270atl.htm |title=Carolina Panthers at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 December 27th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> In a 38\u201310 win over the Tampa Bay Buccaneers during the regular season finale, Newton tied his season-best completion percentage (80.8), threw for almost 300 yards and added a pair of touchdowns and had his first game with two rushing touchdowns since Week 12 of the 2012 season. His passer rating of 139.3 was the second best mark he posted all season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201601030car.htm |title=Tampa Bay Buccaneers at Carolina Panthers \u2013 January 3rd, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> For his efforts, he was named the NFC Offensive Player of the Week for the fifth time in the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000618210/article/cam-newton-highlights-week-17-players-of-week |title=Cam Newton highlights Week 17 Players of Week |website=NFL.com |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> Newton became the first player to win five NFC Offensive Player of the Week awards in a nine-week span within a season and his five awards tied for the most in a season in NFL history ([[Tom Brady]], 2007).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.catscratchreader.com/2016/1/6/10723672/newton-wins-5th-player-of-the-week-award-of-2015-season |title=Newton Wins 5th Player of the Week Award of 2015 Season |last=Jaxon |date=January 6, 2016 |website=Cat Scratch Reader |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> Cam Newton led NFL quarterbacks in rushing attempts, rushing yards, and rushing touchdowns in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.playerprofiler.com/nfl/cam-newton |title=Cam Newton Advanced Stats and Metrics Profile: Rushing Production |website=PlayerProfiler.com}}</ref> Newton's 45 total touchdowns during the regular season marked the most touchdowns by a single player since 2013. Newton was selected as the 2015 [[National Football League Most Valuable Player Award|NFL MVP]] and Offensive Player of the Year by the [[Pro Football Writers Association|PFWA]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/PFWAwriters/status/689870369298223104 |title=Pro Football Writers |website=Twitter |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nNewton and the Panthers finished the season with a 15\u20131 record, a franchise best, and earned a first-round bye in the playoffs. They defeated the [[2015 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]] in the [[2015\u201316 NFL playoffs#NFC: Carolina Panthers 31, Seattle Seahawks 24|Divisional Round]] by a score of 31\u201324, despite nearly blowing a 31\u20130 lead, and went on to defeat the [[2015 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]] 49\u201315 in the [[2015\u201316 NFL playoffs#NFC: Carolina Panthers 49, Arizona Cardinals 15|NFC Championship]] game to face the [[2015 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] in [[Super Bowl 50]]. In the NFC championship game, Newton completed 19 of 28 passes for 335 yards, with two touchdowns and one interception. He also rushed 10 times for 47 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/arizona-cardinals-carolina-panthers-20160124029/ |title=Arizona at Carolina \u2013 2016-01-24 \u2013 National Football League \u2013 Yahoo! Sports |website=Yahoo Sports |access-date=February 8, 2016}}</ref> The Panthers' 49 points were the highest in NFC Championship history.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.panthers.com/news/playoffs.html |title=Carolina Panthers |website=Carolina Panthers |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227223859/http://www.panthers.com/news/playoffs.html |archive-date=February 27, 2018 |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:DeMarcus Ware and Cam Newton Super Bowl 50.jpg|thumb|250px|Newton in [[Super Bowl 50]] against the [[2015 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]].]]\nOn February 6, 2016, Newton was named [[National Football League Most Valuable Player Award|NFL MVP]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/panthers/2016/02/06/cam-newton-mvp-award-carolina/79944880/ |title=Cam Newton named NFL MVP |last=Reyes |first=Lorenzo |date=February 6, 2016 |work=USA Today |access-date=February 6, 2016}}</ref> In Super Bowl 50 on February 7, 2016, which pitted the Panthers' top-ranked offense against the [[Denver Broncos]]' top-ranked defense, the Panthers lost by a score of 24\u201310. The game was generally a one-score affair until a few minutes left in the fourth quarter. The defense of both teams performed extremely well and led to both offenses struggling terribly throughout the game. Newton was sacked six times and Manning was sacked 5 times, both quarterbacks fumbled twice, and both threw an interception.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201602070den.htm |title=Super Bowl 50 \u2013 Denver Broncos vs. Carolina Panthers \u2013 February 7th, 2016 |website=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]] |access-date=August 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000634371/article/broncos-outlast-panthers-claim-sb50-title |title=Broncos outlast Panthers, claim third Super Bowl title |date=July 21, 2015 |website=NFL.com |access-date=August 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/liveupdate/gamecenter/56834/DEN_Gamebook.pdf |title=Super Bowl 50 \u2013 National Football League Game Summary |website=NFL.com |access-date=August 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nNewton was ranked as the top player in the NFL by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2016]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2016/0ap3000000673257/Top-100-Players-of-2016-No-1-Cam-Newton |title='Top 100 Players of 2016': No. 2 Tom Brady |website=NFL.com}}</ref> For the season, Newton has sold the 7th most merchandise from March 2015 to February 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://myfox8.com/2016/04/25/cam-newton-is-nfls-no-7-player-in-merchandise-sales/ |title=Cam Newton is NFL\u2019s No. 7 player in merchandise sales |date=April 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2016 season===\n[[File:Cam Newton 2016.JPG|thumb|upright|Newton in 2016.]]\nIn the opening game of the 2016 season, in a Super Bowl 50 rematch against the [[2016 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]], Newton surpassed two of [[Steve Young]]'s NFL records, one for the most career rushing touchdowns by a quarterback, with his 44th, and the other for most games with a passing and rushing touchdown, with his 32nd.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2016/09/08/carolina-panthers-cam-newton-rushing-touchdowns-record |title=Newton sets record for most rushing TDs by a QB |date=September 9, 2016 |publisher=si.com |access-date=September 15, 2016}}</ref> This also tied [[Otto Graham]]'s all-time professional American football mark of 44 rushing touchdowns by a quarterback.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.foxsports.com/nfl/story/cam-newton-breaks-a-touchdown-record-held-by-steve-young-in-first-half-090816 |title=Cam Newton breaks a touchdown record held by Steve Young in first half |last=Ingrassia |first=Nunzio |date=September 9, 2016 |publisher=Fox Sports |access-date=September 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/football/news/panthers-cam-newton-passes-runs-for-scores-in-opening-night-loss/ |title=Panthers' Cam Newton: Passes, runs for scores in Opening Night loss |publisher=cbssports.com |access-date=September 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn October 2, in a loss at the [[2016 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]], Newton suffered a concussion on a two-point conversion run and missed the rest of the game. Newton also missed the next game against the [[2016 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]].\n\nOn December 4, against the [[2016 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]], Newton was benched for the first offensive series for a dress code violation. It was Newton's first professional game, other than his first career preseason game in 2011, in which he began the game as the backup.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201612040sea.htm |title=Carolina Panthers at Seattle Seahawks \u2013 December 4th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2016 season, Newton completed 52.9 percent of his passes, marking a career worst in that category. He threw 19 touchdown passes, 16 less than the previous year, and 14 interceptions, the second most of his career behind his rookie season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/N/NewtCa00/gamelog/2016 |title=Cam Newton 2016 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> The Panthers regressed from their 15\u20131 record from the previous year to a 6\u201310 record in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/car/2016.htm |title=2016 Carolina Panthers Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> Despite a down 2016 season, Newton was still ranked 44th by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2017]].<ref name=\"nfl\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2017/0ap3000000811950/Top-100-Players-of-2017-No-44-Cam-Newton |title='Top 100 Players of 2017': No. 44 Cam Newton \u2013 NFL Videos |website=nfl.com |access-date=November 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2017 season===\nOn March 30, Newton had surgery to repair a partially torn rotator cuff on his throwing shoulder.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/18969007/carolina-panthers-qb-cam-newton-shoulder-surgery |title=Panthers' Cam Newton to have shoulder surgery, to miss OTAs |last=Newton |first=David |date=March 21, 2017 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=December 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000796371/article/cam-newton-recovering-after-shoulder-surgery |title=Cam Newton recovering after shoulder surgery |last=Sessler |first=Marc |date=March 30, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=March 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring a press conference on October 4, Newton was asked a question by Jourdan Rodrigue, a female sportswriter for ''[[The Charlotte Observer]]'', regarding passing routes. Newton smirked and said, \"It's funny to hear a female talk about routes.\" Then he answered her question.<ref name=\"Ripple\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/football/cam-newton-sexist-remark-female-reporter-question-article-1.3541726 |title=Cam Newton makes sexist remark and smirks at female reporter\u2019s question |last=Ripple |first=Zachary |date=October 4, 2017 |work=New York Daily News |access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref> His remarks were viewed as sexist by Rodrigue as well as many in the media.<ref name=Ripple/><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/columnist/nancy-armour/2017/10/04/cam-newton-sexism-is-never-funny/734486001/ |title=Contrary to what Carolina Panthers quarterback Cam Newton says, sexism isn't funny |last=Armour |first=Nancy |date=October 5, 2017 |work=USA Today |access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.startribune.com/on-cam-newton-a-funny-question-and-a-sexist-response/449577423/ |title=On Cam Newton, a 'funny' question and a sexist response |last=Rand |first=Michael |date=October 5, 2017 |work=Star Tribune |access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref> It later surfaced that Rodrigue had previously mocked Newton using a [[Twitter]] account with which she had also posted racist comments, causing the publication BlackSportsOnline.com to label her a hypocrite.<ref name=\"racist\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/racist-cam-newton-reporter-jourdan-rodrigue-tweeted-n-word-issues-apology-2597847 |title='Racist' Cam Newton Reporter Jourdan Rodrigue Tweeted N-Word, Issues Apology |last=Vultaggio |first=Maria |date=October 5, 2017 |work=International Business Times |access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref> The following day, yogurt company [[Dannon]] dropped Newton as a sponsor.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/panthers/2017/10/05/dannon-cut-ties-panthers-quarterback-cam-newton/735648001/ |title=Dannon cuts ties with Panthers quarterback Cam Newton |last=Perez |first=A.J. |date=October 5, 2017 |work=USA Today |access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://nytimes.com/2017/10/05/sports/football/cam-newton-dannon-sponsorship.html |title=Cam Newton Loses Dannon Sponsorship Deal After Sexist Remarks |last=Hoffman |first=Benjamin |date=October 5, 2017 |work=The New York Times |access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref> Newton uploaded a video to Twitter later that day in which he apologized for his remarks.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/05/sports/football/cam-newton-dannon-sponsorship.html |title=Cam Newton Apologizes for Sexist Remarks |last=Hoffman |first=Benjamin |date=October 5, 2017 |work=The New York Times |access-date=October 6, 2017}}</ref> During ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' against the [[2017 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]] in Week 10, Newton threw for 254 yards and rushed for 95 yards with four total touchdowns. The Panthers combined for 294 rushing yards and 548 total yards of offense as the Panthers won 45\u201321.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000877272/article/cam-newton-runs-panthers-evolved-offense-perfectly |title=Cam Newton runs Panthers' evolved offense perfectly |last=Harmon |first=Matt |date=November 14, 2017 |publisher=NFL.com |access-date=November 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000877240/article/cam-newton-leads-panthers-reborn-run-game-to-win |title=Cam Newton leads Panthers' reborn run game to win |last=Bergman |first=Jeremy |date=November 13, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=November 14, 2017}}</ref> His performance in Week 10 earned him NFC Offensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000877642/article/tom-brady-cam-newton-among-players-of-the-week |title=Tom Brady, Cam Newton among Players of the Week |last=Maya |first=Adam |date=November 15, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref> He finished the regular season with 3,302 passing yards, 22 touchdowns, 16 interceptions and a career-high 754 rushing yards to go along with six rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/N/NewtCa00/gamelog/2017 |title=Cam Newton 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> The Panthers made the playoffs as the #5-seed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2017 |title=2017 NFL Standings & Team Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs#NFC: New Orleans Saints 31, Carolina Panthers 26|Wild Card Round]] against the [[2017 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]], he was 24 of 40 for 349 yards and two touchdowns as the Panthers lost by a score of 31\u201326.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801070nor.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Carolina Panthers at New Orleans Saints \u2013 January 7th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 27, 2018}}</ref> Newton was ranked 25th by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2018]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2018/0ap3000000936763/Top-100-Players-of-2018-Cam-Newton-No-25 |title='Top 100 Players of 2018': Carolina Panthers quarterback Cam Newton |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u201319: Injury-shortened seasons===\n[[File:Cam Newton (45327735431).jpg|thumb|250px|Newton in 2018]]\nAfter a 16\u20138 victory over the [[2018 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]] in Week 1 of the 2018 season, Newton went 32 of 45 passing, 335 passing yards, three touchdowns, and an interception to go along with 42 rushing yards in the 31\u201324 loss to the [[2018 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/sports/spt-columns-blogs/scott-fowler/article218336470.html |title=Scott Says: Hurricane remnants in Charlotte make Panthers\u2019 loss to Falcons feel weird |last=Fowler |first=Scott |date=September 16, 2018 |work=Charlotte Observer |access-date=October 6, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> The next week, he passed for two touchdowns and ran for two touchdowns in the 31\u201321 victory over the [[2018 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2018/09/23/newtons-4-tds-lift-panthers-over-bengals-31-21/37912747/ |title=Newton's 4 TDs lift Panthers over Bengals 31\u201321 |date=September 23, 2018 |work=USA TODAY |access-date=October 6, 2018 |agency=Associated Press |language=en}}</ref> In Week 7 against the [[2018 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], after being down 17\u20130 in the fourth quarter, Newton completed 16 of 22 passes for 201 yards and two touchdowns in the final quarter as the Panthers defeated the Eagles 21\u201317, earning him NFC Offensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000977807/article/cam-newton-aaron-donald-among-players-of-the-week |title=Cam Newton, Aaron Donald among Players of the Week |date=October 24, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nNewton and the Panthers began struggling in the month of November. After the Panthers lost to the [[2018 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]] in Week 15, which was their sixth straight loss after starting 6\u20132, Newton acknowledged a nagging shoulder injury that had been hampering his play during the losing streak, and hinted that the team would deactivate him for the final two games of the season in order to heal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/car/2018.htm |title=2018 Carolina Panthers Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/cam-newton-opens-up-on-shoulder-injury-after-latest-loss-acknowledges-panthers-could-shut-him-down/ |title=Cam Newton opens up on shoulder injury after latest loss, acknowledges Panthers could shut him down |last=Wagner-McGough |first=Sean |date=December 18, 2018 |publisher=CBS Sports |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/25772192 |title=With Cam hurt, Panthers keeping 'options open' |last=Newton |first=David |date=January 16, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref> On January 24, 2019, Newton officially underwent right shoulder surgery.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001013126/article/panthers-cam-newton-undergoes-shoulder-surgery |title=Cam Newton undergoes shoulder surgery |last=Bergman |first=Jeremy |date=January 24, 2019 |publisher=NFL.com |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a poll orchestrated by writers from ''[[The Athletic]]'', Newton was voted the most underrated quarterback in the league by 85 defensive players from 25 teams.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pantherswire.usatoday.com/2019/01/10/cam-newton-polls-as-nfls-most-underrated-qb-by-defensive-players/ |title=Cam Newton polls as NFL's most underrated QB by defensive players |last=Weaver |first=Tim |date=January 10, 2019 |website=Panthers Wire |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref> He was ranked 87th by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2019]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2019/0ap3000001036752/Top-100-Players-of-2019-Cam-Newton-No-87 |title='Top 100 Players of 2019': Carolina Panthers quarterback Cam Newton |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=August 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nNewton made his return from injury in Week 1 of the following season against the [[2019 Los Angeles Rams|Los Angeles Rams]]. In the game, Newton passed for 239 yards and one interception as the Panthers lost 30\u201327.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127923 |title=Goff, Gurley lead Rams to 30-27 win over Panthers |date=September 8, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=September 8, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In Week 2 against the [[2019 Tampa Bay Buccaneers|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] on ''Thursday Night Football'', Newton completed 25 passes out of 51 attempts for 333 yards as the Panthers lost 20\u201314.  After the game, Newton said \"All fingers are pointed back to the offense and me specifically.\" <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128054 |title=Bucs use goal-line stand to beat Panthers 20-14 |date=September 13, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=September 13, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Newton was held out of the week 3 game against the [[2019 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]] due to injury, and it was later revealed that he had a [[Lisfranc fracture]], which he later confirmed in a [[YouTube]] vlog.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/09/27/cam-newton-says-he-just-needs-some-time-to-get-right/ |title=Cam Newton says he just needs some time \"to get right\" |last=Williams |first=Charean |date=September 27, 2019 |website=ProFootballTalk |language=en |access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eIGAECpWNSA |title=The Truth About Why I\u2019m Sidelined: In My Words And Done My Way |date=September 27, 2019 |last=Newton |first=Cam |type=Video |publisher=YouTube |work=Cam Newton Vlogs}}</ref> On November 5, the Panthers placed Newton on injured reserve as the injury was healing slower than expected.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.panthers.com/news/panthers-place-quarterback-cam-newton-on-injured-reserve-foot |title=Panthers place Cam Newton on injured reserve |date=November 5, 2019 |website=Carolina Panthers |access-date=November 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, 2020 the Panthers announced they had given Newton permission to seek a trade.<ref>{{cite web|title=Panthers give Cam Newton permission to seek trade|url=https://www.panthers.com/news/panthers-give-cam-newton-permission-to-seek-trade|website=Panthers.com|date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> However, on March 24, 2020, after failing to find a trade partner, the team announced they had officially released Newton.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.panthers.com/news/carolina-panthers-release-qb-cam-newton|title=Carolina Panthers release QB Cam Newton|website=Panthers.com|language=en-US|access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==NFL career statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n! colspan=\"2\"|Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#FFFF00; width:3em;\"|\n| AP [[NFL MVP]]\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n|Career high\n|}\n\n===Regular season===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align